WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:22.000
Today is Monday September 26, 2011. My name is Joe Manier of the Southern Oral History Program.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:29.000
At the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, I'm with the videographer John W. Walker Bishop in Little Rock, Arkansas, Arkansas,

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:42.000
to do an oral history interview for the Civil Rights History Project, which is a joint undertaking of the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:48.000
And we're very privileged today to be with Ms. Carrie Lamar, young in Little Rock, Arkansas at her home.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:53.000
And this young thank you very much for the warm welcome. That's nice to be with your little privilege.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:55.000
I'm very honored. Thank you.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:05.000
Let me start. If I could, with having you talk just a little bit about your family, your community, coming up in Barton, Arkansas.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:23.000
Okay. Well, my parents, Lazarus Lamar and my mom, Lytte Lamar, gave birth to four girls, two boys, which I was the youngest of the four girls.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:34.000
I don't remember actually living at Barton. I remember living at Lexa, which was about four or five miles from Barton.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:50.000
And we lived there in Lexa until I was, I think, 14. And we lived, moved to West Helena, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:02:16.000
But doing my stay in Lexa, we actually did sharecropping, raised our own gardens, raised our own cows, chickens, hogs, worked the cotton fields.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:21.000
That was before soybeans came in. So I was glad to see soybeans.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:27.000
Then I had to pick so much cotton, the chop so much cotton.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:39.000
We had our own depot where the train came through and we could catch the train and ride the train from Lexa to hell on a down on Cherry Street and do our shopping and stuff.

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:48.000
That was exciting. And we all, all the children always got a chance to go with mom when she went shopping in hell on her.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:55.000
Tell me a little bit about your parents as a person.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:07.000
Well, my dad, he was, I think he went through the third grade, but educationally speaking, he was a real sharp man, very smart.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:14.000
He loved math. He worked in an ice plant that we had in Lexa.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:20.000
And didn't do much work with us and the field mom was in the field with us.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:28.000
She was a midwife. She delivered most of the babies in our area.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:44.000
And not just any midwife either, but she was the midwife that if there was a breach baby coming into the world, people would come and find her because she had that skill in our hands.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:53.000
I call it the laying on her hands. That she knew how to manipulate the womb and get that baby to turn around so it could come out right now.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:58.000
When I was 23, I found out that my mom didn't know how to read or write.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:07.000
She was actually able to conceal that from me. I don't know if the rest of the children knew it or not, but she was able to conceal that from me until I was 23.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:14.000
Did they come up in that area? The Delta Arkansas, that were their families.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:28.000
When my mom was born in Yazoo City, Mississippi, and my dad was born in Palestine, Arkansas, which is right outside of Forest City between Memphis and Brinkley.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:44.000
And my dad and mom both grew up on plantations, which one of my uncles gave me some real depth information about their history and what they names were before it became Lamar.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:54.000
Most black people don't like to talk about that. They kind of keep it hush hush because they don't want to identify what they pass.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:05:05.000
Most of the elders in my family because of my participation in the civil rights movement, they felt like I needed all about our family that they could share with me.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:14.000
So my uncle Virgil, who was, he worked in the steel mills in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania for years.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:20.000
And when he would come home, you know, he was like, I'll tell you whatever you want to know, you know, just ask.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:31.000
So that's what I did. And learning a lot of things about my dad's side of the family from their plantation name was Raymond.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:41.000
But once they left the plantation, my great-great-grandfather changed their name to Lamar, where he came up with Lamar, my uncle didn't know that.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:51.000
But he did share that much with me. And my dad came from a family of like ten sisters and twelve, it was twelve boys.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:06:00.000
And my grandfather lived with us for a while when we was in Lexington. He lived to be like 104 before he passed away.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:13.000
And my mom's side of the family, I really didn't know that many of them. Her dad, I know that last time mom died when he was pretty young.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:22.000
So she had a sister in Memphis named Fannie Brown. And both of her brothers lived in West Helena, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:34.000
Well, when I lived at Barton, James Bell lived at Barton. And George Bell lived in West Helena, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas. And that's a slew of children.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:39.000
I mean, a large, large family, but close.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:50.000
Your grandfather lived to be 104? And you said he lived with you when you were a child. So depending on when he presumed, and that he had been born from the 18th.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:07:04.000
In 1818, because he died about 1960. It was in 1960 something.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:12.000
He whittled too. He whittled and made us rings and musical instruments. He would make us rings out of buttons and stuff like that.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:20.000
And make us flutes out of the bamboo stalks or stems, whatever you call them.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:29.000
So we looked forward to him coming there spending time with us. He spent so many months with us. And then I had an aunt named Amy Bessie.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:42.000
That her name was Bessie Lipsy, L.I.P.S.C. White. And they lived out in an area called LaGrange L.A. Capital G.R.A. and G.E.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:51.000
And she had like 13 children. Well, he would stay with them sometime. And then he would come and stay with us sometime.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:08:02.000
And we looked forward to that. There was always awesome time. A lot of our family had moved to Chicago in the spring. And some of them would come visit us.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:07.000
We just looked forward to that. That was like Christmas for us.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:13.000
Tell me about your home and where exactly you lived in LaGrange?

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:28.000
Okay. My home in Lexa was a triplex shotgun house. I mean, it was three houses in one building. But all three houses were shotgun units.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:40.000
We lived on one end. It was a single lady named Miss Mary that lived in the middle. And then the Walker family lived on the other end. The Walker family had about a husband and wife and 14 children.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:58.000
And they all lived in those three rooms. It was really rural. My dad hunted mostly in one of the time for the meats that we ate.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:11.000
At that time in our life, we still had smoke houses. So when somebody killed slaughtered a hog or a cow, they would get together and do that.

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:26.000
And the backyard would be full of those big old cast iron pots that set over stack of wood or whatever had like the three legs on it.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:41.000
And we cleaned chitlins, washed, we had number three tub just lined up. You get all the waste out of one on one to rinse them into the other one, take them over to the other one and today got pearly white.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:57.000
And I mean, you could see like an open ring. You could see those colors in the entrails after they were cleaned. We did cracklings right out there where you would take that fat back and throw it over in the grease.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:08.000
We actually created its own grease. You just put it in a hot pot. And after a while, the grease would begin to bubble on the top and then cracklings would float up to the top.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:12.000
And I mean, you know, that was just a heyday.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:39.000
How about school? School was, it was necessary. It was important. It was significant in our lives. But in my younger years in school, we would get taken out of school to make sure we had ample enough income and supplies and things that we need to get us through the winter.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:58.000
So the books that we had, most of them didn't have backs on them. Pages were missing because we would get the books that had barred in high school, stamped down on them and something like that or another school.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:03.000
And that's what we had to do our studies from.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:15.000
I guess I got a little bit fortunate because of me being the youngest girl. When my sister that's a year older me started to school, I started to school too.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:30.000
So I got to jump start on everything and being a girl too in my age, I didn't get pulled out of school as much as some of my other siblings did because I couldn't do what they could do.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:45.000
So I helped Mama to quilt to can. I got chance to watch over 300 fruit jars every year and make sure that, you know, we had food can to get us through the winter.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:53.000
Pick pecans, walnuts, the black walnuts, I love black walnuts today.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:12:18.000
How did you parents? I was about to ask how your circumstances like that. How did parents help you all the children come to understand how to navigate through Jim Crow, how to be alert to the things that you needed to be alert to.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:24.000
And how did you get a burden to tell you directly today?

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:34.000
I guess a lot of it was exposure and observing how they handle situations.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:52.000
And I was the child that my oldest sister named me Minerva because I didn't have a problem asking questions or adventuring out.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:13:18.000
And usually when we asked our mom about situations, she would always refer us to the Bible. And I think there may have been one thing that kind of covered up her lack of education for me because to me she had so much wisdom and so much knowledge about different things that I just assumed she could read and write.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:25.000
And she stayed on top of us to make sure that we could read and write, you know.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:32.000
But she always, one thing she taught me, she said, don't ever be afraid to ask anybody for anything.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:37.000
If you need something, ask for it. There's only one or two answers you're going to get this. Yes and no.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:47.000
So when I needed something, I'd jump over that fear that would come up and go for it. And usually I was blessed.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:58.000
So I knew instinctively because I had a couple of experiences that went on in our community.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:05.000
Well one night I noticed my daddy left home with a gun and I knew he wasn't going hunting.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:11.000
And I asked him where he was going. He said, oh me and the boys were going to hunt some combs.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:22.000
And when he got to the end of the road, he just all of a sudden disappeared. Then I found out later that it was a situation that went on that day where I wanted to

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:34.000
merchant daughters in the town had accused one of the young black boys of raping or well asking her to have sex with him.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:42.000
And the father that son had went and handled the situation the best he knew how to handle it with her family.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:54.000
But something happened that they didn't feel like they needed to take a chance and leave this child to be exposed to whatever might happen once the son went down.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:15:04.000
So they guarded the entrance to the community that night by them. They just loaded up both sides of the road with people with shotguns to protect this young man.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:16.000
Plus the young man that she accused, he was shy and probably had some special needs that was going on in his life.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:25.000
And it took me years to get my daddy to finally share that information with me of what actually happened that night.

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:33.000
You said there were other things you remember too about incidents as you were going there?

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:46.000
Oh, one, in Lexa where we lived in years that I could remember, I'd say from five years until I was about 13 or 14.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:16:03.000
We used to work in the fields and some of the people that we worked for, that white people that was poor like we were, they worked out there then there was every night in Mexicans and Chinese were working out there which always thought was strange.

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:08.000
But they came in from somewhere in cotton.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:22.000
And one of the young girls, me and her was about the same age. She's always had these conversations with me about what blacks were and weren't and what white people were and weren't and stuff like that.

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:32.000
And when they me and her was having a little altercation up in cotton wagon, my daddy just happened to be walking by when I was getting rid of it.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:37.000
And I actually picked up, I was fixing the throw over the wagon.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:55.000
And I did it was like cat. And I put it down and we had exchanged some words, you know, I did some old old science jokes with the call the dozens, you know how you would put people down and stuff.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:17:01.000
And I had exchanged all those words and I had got passed that I was just ready to get rid of her, you know.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:04.000
Of course the Lord sent my dad by to take care of that.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:12.000
And years later, believe it or not, before my dad passed, I ran into this girl again. She worked for Western Union.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:16.000
And she was holding up the old black people in Helena, Arkansas.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:25.000
This is in the late 80s.

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:32.000
And the Western Union closes promptly. Whatever they close in time is, you know, they're going to close down south.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:35.000
I walked in there with my dad. He was on a Saturday morning.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:45.000
And he was about six people in the line, about 20 minutes to 12. And she was sitting there on the phone talk.

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:52.000
And I said, these people need to be waited on. He was like, yeah, he's saying they close at 12 o'clock.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:56.000
And we was going up there to get some money that he was waiting on.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:18:00.000
So I walked up to the counter, you know, me and my little bowl cell.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:04.000
That's excuse me. I'd be with you in the mini-man.

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:11.000
Okay. I go back. She keep right on top. We didn't even look up at the people.

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:14.000
She just on the phone with her little conversation.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:18.000
So I went back up. That's excuse me. That's what time do you close?

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:23.000
She's at 12 o'clock. I said, when 12 o'clock come, you're going to leave, right?

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:26.000
That's usually the procedure. That's what let me tell you something.

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:31.000
You don't get up out of that chair right now. You won't be sitting in it. Come mind him on.

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:38.000
And she put that phone down. And all the people in there was like, who is this woman?

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:42.000
So when we left my dad and said, do you know who that was?

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:45.000
And I went, no, I don't know. I don't care. I was bad.

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:53.000
You know, I was just really, he said, you remember the wounds that lived in Lexa?

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:58.000
I said, the wounds. He said, yeah, you know the little girl you was going to pitch out the wagon.

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:02.000
And I said, you're a kid. He said, that was her.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:07.000
I said, she hadn't learned anything yet, actually.

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:10.000
Still don't respect people.

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:16.000
Did Lexa have, did you, you lived in sort of a small town?

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:22.000
Did Lexa have a specific racial geography?

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:26.000
There was a demarcation called the Rural Tracks.

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:36.000
And on one side of the track was the, on our side, the black side was the train station.

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:43.000
You called it from our side. And next to that, at one time we had like a cafe

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:50.000
was across the streets from the train station. So when people were waiting their heads on where they could go sitting.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:56.000
We had a little garage because a few people had trucks, you know.

00:19:56.000 --> 00:20:03.000
They used them for farming and stuff. And then around them, being over here was the Muscleini family

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:09.000
that basically raised all of the vegetables and things for safe way.

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:14.000
And you know, the markets that was in West Helena, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas and Helena, Arkansas.

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:18.000
And I think they were a German family.

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:24.000
And we did most of our farming. We did with them.

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:28.000
Because you know, you tried to pick the nicer people to work with.

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:35.000
It was another man we used to work for. His name was Homer Tiles. I loved that man. He was a sweet man.

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:41.000
He used to protect me at the way scales because I couldn't pick cotton, a bunch cotton.

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:51.000
I was blessed to pick 100 pounds. And if you didn't get 100 pounds of cotton, in my family you got a weapon right there under the scales.

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:55.000
So I got frequent weapons under the scale.

00:20:55.000 --> 00:21:01.000
And a lot of times he would be standing there begging my mom and not to whip me.

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:07.000
So cotton season when we was picking cotton, that was my favorite time of the year.

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:15.000
I didn't like that at all. And that was like my motivation to graduate from high school and leave.

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:18.000
And that's exactly what I did.

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:24.000
How long did the cotton season last?

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:36.000
Normally, I would say, I'm trying to think, is it the August?

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:46.000
We would go start picking cotton sometime. It would go through the fall school season until it got too cold.

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:56.000
Depending on how big the owner's property was. And when it got cold, they did what they called snap cotton or pull cotton.

00:21:56.000 --> 00:22:02.000
They would just take the birds and all and leave it to the gin to separate the holes from the cotton.

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:08.000
But before that, you had to get your fingers down in the bulb and pull the cotton out.

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:13.000
Because you didn't have cuticles, they were gone.

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:16.000
And that was my nightmare.

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:20.000
What was the typical day or week in cotton picking season?

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:22.000
Signed up to sundown.

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:25.000
And you were lucky as you said you could get an unkind.

00:22:25.000 --> 00:22:27.000
Because you were...

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:28.000
I was small.

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:33.000
For I was picking it and what they call a foot tub.

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:40.000
I would pick it and put it in there and then when they get too heavy for me to actually pick it up, I'd take it and give it to my mom.

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:49.000
And then they had seven foot sacks and they had three foot sacks.

00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:52.000
When I did get big enough for a sack, that's what I started.

00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:54.000
It was like a three footer.

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:57.000
And it would take me all day long to let things up.

00:22:57.000 --> 00:23:01.000
And it wasn't a hundred pounds of cotton when I got through with it.

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:03.000
And I'd be working hard.

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:04.000
But it was just...

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:09.000
You know, as I grew up, I would tell my mom, my hands is not made for picking cotton.

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:11.000
I didn't manchoppin it.

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:14.000
But picking it just wasn't me.

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:17.000
Where were your brothers and age in relation to you?

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:21.000
My youngest brother, he was three years younger than me.

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:24.000
And my oldest brother was five years older than me.

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:30.000
So typically when you started working in cotton harvest, there would have been five children picking.

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:33.000
And then one younger brother.

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:36.000
And what... do you remember what you got paid?

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:41.000
I remember like three fifty a day.

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:44.000
That was my like highest I can remember.

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:49.000
That was for chopping, getting the grass up and around and everything.

00:23:49.000 --> 00:23:57.000
And paying you per hundred pounds was something about three dollars for a hundred pounds of cotton.

00:23:57.000 --> 00:24:03.000
Then as soon as I left, got out of high school, everything went to ten and twelve dollars.

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:05.000
I was upset about that.

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:08.000
I said, but you know what? One thing about it, I don't have to go back there.

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:13.000
Did your mom get fair treatment at the end of the day picking up the weighing station?

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:15.000
I don't think so.

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:20.000
Now when we got big enough that we knew how to add knowledge, that was my job.

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:27.000
I had to keep everybody's weight when they go up there and me and the owner had to job.

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:34.000
Of course, you didn't get to argue with him too much about what your totals were versus his totals.

00:24:34.000 --> 00:24:38.000
With Mr. Home I could do that.

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:42.000
And your father, you said work at the ice plant?

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:45.000
What was his job like?

00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:50.000
Did you know how they used to make the hundred pound block size? That's what he did.

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:51.000
In Lexington.

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:54.000
And he also worked at the gin.

00:24:54.000 --> 00:25:02.000
So at the gin, the waste cotton that was there, my mom would use that to make quills for the bed and the pillows, stuff like that.

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:06.000
What was your job's job at the cotton gin?

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:08.000
He ginned the cotton.

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:16.000
And he knew how to clean the little folk's things that went around and around to separate the cotton from the hulls.

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:18.000
He could do all of it.

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:29.000
But basically, he was the one up in the thing that would pull that suction part down and get the cotton out of the trailers.

00:25:29.000 --> 00:25:32.000
I haven't asked you yet about church.

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:36.000
Church was, I enjoyed it.

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:38.000
I would when nobody else would go.

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:41.000
I would be up every Sunday morning ready to go.

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:43.000
I liked to sing.

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:51.000
There was one pastor that used to come and get my mom to let me go to church with him doing his revival time.

00:25:51.000 --> 00:25:58.000
And I would sing for him and the ladies would get happy and thought he'd purses at me and scare me.

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:02.000
I did that with him probably from time I was five.

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:06.000
I was about nine years old.

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:09.000
And then my mom stopped letting me go for some reason.

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:12.000
I guess I was growing up.

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:18.000
I may have said something to her that said it's time for her not to go anymore.

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:20.000
What was the church?

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:25.000
I grew up, our family church was first Baptist church Alexa.

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:29.000
Reverend Devaro was our pastor.

00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:34.000
And Mr. I think his name was Gus Wilburn.

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:36.000
He was our superintendent.

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:38.000
He would go and ring the church bell.

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:45.000
And they lived across the field for months about as far as from my house he was from that house over there.

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:49.000
And it was a big old walnut tree that sat in between our houses.

00:26:49.000 --> 00:26:52.000
That was my favorite spot.

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:55.000
And when he went to church I went to church.

00:26:55.000 --> 00:26:57.000
When he'd ring that bell I'd gone on up there.

00:26:57.000 --> 00:26:59.000
I said, Mom can I go to church now?

00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:01.000
And she said yeah go ahead on.

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:03.000
And I'd go up there.

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:05.000
I'd get a chance to play the piano.

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:08.000
I could play the piano by ear.

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:10.000
And just had a good time.

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:14.000
And then there was another lady named Miss Molly Richardson.

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:20.000
She used to have a sunshine band in her backyard every Saturday evening.

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:25.000
And she sat on a hill and we had cool eight and cookies.

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:31.000
And then there was another lady named Miss Koramartin.

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:38.000
She used to do the Sacramento bread and wines once a month.

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:46.000
So the Saturday before we had that after I got up pretty good side I would go spend Saturday with her.

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:49.000
And I put it get all that stuff prepared.

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:53.000
We had a lot of fun and wake up everybody in the community laugh.

00:27:53.000 --> 00:27:58.000
They would say, Kettle with Martin's house.

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:10.000
So that was my Christian experience was something awesome that I didn't really understand until I was about 45 I guess.

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:18.000
And it came after about five or ten years of seeking what salvation was all about.

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:24.000
And I realized that I had probably been saved since I was like four years old.

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:27.000
But I just didn't understand fully what it was all about.

00:28:27.000 --> 00:28:29.000
I'm sure we'll come back to that thing.

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:33.000
I want to ask you too about Phillips County, Arkansas.

00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:40.000
That was obviously the location of the Elaine Massacre.

00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:43.000
1919.

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:53.000
I wonder if was that a part of your awareness as a child that the county had that specific history of a race massacre?

00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:58.000
It came up probably when I was in my middle teens.

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:00.000
We were working down there.

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:07.000
And one of the things I noticed was the earth was cracked and it was hard.

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:12.000
At the temperature outside was in the 80s and 90s.

00:29:12.000 --> 00:29:17.000
It was like the ground would just crack like parchment.

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:22.000
And when your whole hit it was like, Ding! Something like that.

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:25.000
And I was like, why has this ground so hard?

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:28.000
I just, I hated to go down there.

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:33.000
And after a while with the children complaining, they would begin to tell us about

00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:36.000
the earth.

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:39.000
It's probably from the blood that's in the earth.

00:29:39.000 --> 00:29:42.000
It was like, why is it blood in the earth?

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:45.000
And they shared with us about the massacre down there.

00:29:45.000 --> 00:29:48.000
And the race right and everything.

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:52.000
Was anybody in the community active in the NAACP?

00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:56.000
Not in West Helena, Arkansas that I was aware of.

00:29:56.000 --> 00:30:02.000
Personally, I never heard of the NAACP until about 1965.

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:04.000
Right.

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:09.000
Well, I didn't see, I started working with SNCC around 1965.

00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:13.000
1957 when they had the the Little Rock Nine.

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:19.000
Even though I lived two hours away in today's transportation system.

00:30:19.000 --> 00:30:23.000
If the news came then, I'd never heard anything about it.

00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:25.000
We didn't have TV.

00:30:25.000 --> 00:30:31.000
We had our first electricity in our house in 1958.

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:34.000
And it was over there.

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:37.000
But didn't come up at church.

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:40.000
And no black newspaper in the community.

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:44.000
And your mother, as you said, couldn't leave you.

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:45.000
Right.

00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:49.000
Tell me about, you mentioned earlier that you had a strong sense,

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:55.000
even as a child of 10, 12-ish, that you didn't want to spend your life in that world

00:30:55.000 --> 00:30:58.000
that you wanted to graduate from high school and go on.

00:30:58.000 --> 00:31:04.000
And you said a little bit more about, did you have a sense of what going on from there might mean?

00:31:04.000 --> 00:31:05.000
I really did.

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:10.000
And I just knew that the life I was living in that wasn't what I wanted to do.

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:14.000
Well, I guess you did say that you had some extended members of your extended family

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:16.000
who would say had gone north to West.

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:17.000
Right.

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:18.000
It was like Pittsburgh.

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:27.000
And I guess in 1961, my oldest sister, she went to Mississippi

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:30.000
to attend Mary Holmes Junior College.

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:36.000
And of course, we all worked diligently to get her in that college.

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:39.000
She went there for two years.

00:31:39.000 --> 00:31:41.000
And she was sick.

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:45.000
But she was a very strong Christian young lady.

00:31:45.000 --> 00:31:50.000
After her second year there, she went to Columbia University in New York City.

00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:53.000
And she was studying there.

00:31:53.000 --> 00:31:55.000
And that was in 1963.

00:31:55.000 --> 00:31:58.000
And she died while she was there.

00:31:58.000 --> 00:32:04.000
And I think that for me, that was like,

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:12.000
it was probably my disconnect from pursuing education at a higher level.

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:17.000
Because even in the schools that I grew up in,

00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:21.000
Black folks have their own look-ass system.

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:26.000
That if you don't look a certain way, and your skin colored and light enough,

00:32:26.000 --> 00:32:29.000
and you don't come from the right family background,

00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:34.000
you get discriminated against as much there as you would in the white community.

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:37.000
So, and that was my experience in school.

00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:43.000
It didn't matter what my grades were or how I excelled in one level or another.

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:48.000
And I had to fight through that in my senior high school play.

00:32:48.000 --> 00:32:54.000
Because, you know, talent speaking, I had the arts.

00:32:54.000 --> 00:32:56.000
I could sing.

00:32:56.000 --> 00:33:02.000
I could memorize what I needed to memorize to get a party in a place.

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:03.000
I'm like that.

00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:06.000
I was good at spelling.

00:33:06.000 --> 00:33:09.000
And I liked competition, you know.

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:15.000
But I got fought so much in that that if you don't want me to excel over here,

00:33:15.000 --> 00:33:18.000
then I'm just not even going to try over here, you know.

00:33:18.000 --> 00:33:22.000
And my worst subject in school was math.

00:33:22.000 --> 00:33:26.000
But fortunately, my teacher was a very nice man.

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:29.000
I know where forgetting his name was William Rush.

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:33.000
And he went on to get a PhD in mathematics.

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:38.000
And after I graduated from high school, I met him when he was writing his thesis.

00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:44.000
And I got to type a thesis for him.

00:33:44.000 --> 00:33:50.000
I will come back to the particular your high school because I really want to talk some more about that.

00:33:50.000 --> 00:33:51.000
Okay.

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:54.000
We're back after just a quick break.

00:33:54.000 --> 00:34:00.000
Let me ask you about, did you mention a moment ago that very little news came into the community

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:03.000
through the 50s anyway and got electricity in the home.

00:34:03.000 --> 00:34:11.000
Did news of the emerging direct action phase of the movement after 1960?

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:13.000
Did that come into your awareness?

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:17.000
Sit ins and protests around the country in the early 60s?

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:23.000
Only because of people like Myrtle Glasgow and Howard Himmelbaum.

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:26.000
Tell me about those folks.

00:34:26.000 --> 00:34:31.000
I think Howard Himmelbaum was the first group to come through then.

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:39.000
He came through with a man named Jim Jones from Louisville, Arkansas.

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:44.000
I think Bill Hansen may have been with them.

00:34:44.000 --> 00:34:47.000
It was four or five of them.

00:34:47.000 --> 00:34:57.000
And they came and got a meeting with one of the local churches to tell, you know, share with us what they were doing and everything.

00:34:57.000 --> 00:35:07.000
At that time, the focus was voter education and trying to abolish poll tax because at that time,

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:11.000
when people went to vote, they had to pay a dollar to register the vote.

00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:13.000
And most of them couldn't even write their name.

00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:18.000
They just did an X and of course they vote probably got flipped on to the side of the minute they turned around.

00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:22.000
If they waited till then, they probably did it in their faces.

00:35:22.000 --> 00:35:26.000
So I went to all these meetings.

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:34.000
And they wanted to know, you know, if I would work with them and all that, and of course, I said, you know, you have to go ask my parents.

00:35:34.000 --> 00:35:38.000
And they did and got permission for me to work with them.

00:35:38.000 --> 00:35:46.000
And I was probably one of the few girls in the community that just stepped up and did.

00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:53.000
So I remember another man that was there, Jerry Casey.

00:35:53.000 --> 00:35:57.000
He was one of the first young men to get involved.

00:35:57.000 --> 00:35:59.000
And at that time, we had moved to West Helena, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas.

00:35:59.000 --> 00:36:00.000
We was not in Lexa.

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:04.000
We moved to West Helena, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas in 1964.

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:13.000
And there was 1965 coming into that school year of 65, 66, I believe.

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:33.000
And the people, especially the black fathers, they were afraid because they knew that that meant the white community was going to begin to backlash on everything that happened.

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:35.000
And the families would have to suffer and stuff.

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:39.000
So my dad was like, you need to be careful messing around with them.

00:36:39.000 --> 00:36:42.000
And he was like, you know, I don't know.

00:36:42.000 --> 00:36:56.000
He was like, you know, I'm just, you know, I just want to protect you.

00:36:56.000 --> 00:37:01.000
And there was a lot of clients.

00:37:01.000 --> 00:37:08.000
And they were very much so they did some drive by,

00:37:08.000 --> 00:37:16.000
what's it called, Molotov cocktails that they do at the Civil Rights Workers' Places where they lived.

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:27.000
And if it hadn't been for like a poll or something that was right there to block it when they threw it, it would have went into the house that happened on several occasions.

00:37:28.000 --> 00:37:37.000
Then they started harassing the Civil Rights Workers by arresting them for being vagrants.

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:39.000
And taking them to jail.

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:42.000
And of course, you know, you had to come up with money.

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:50.000
And they knew that these most of them were either college students or college professors that was just there for the summer, maybe.

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:59.000
But most of them after they got there, they may not have stayed in West Helena, Arkansas, but they went somewhere else and continued to do the work that they were doing there.

00:37:59.000 --> 00:38:06.000
We had people come in as a result of the first group.

00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:14.000
We had a Julian Bond came, Andrew Young, Stokely Carmichael.

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:21.000
I want to say, Eldridge Cleaver and Marion Barry, they came through there.

00:38:21.000 --> 00:38:28.000
Most of them they'd come in like we'd have a meeting for two or three days in a church.

00:38:28.000 --> 00:38:37.000
The other thing they realized when my back, I'm the person that sat on this store front every day.

00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:46.000
Every day, got everybody in West Helena, Arkansas to come by and sign my petition to abolish poll tax.

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:55.000
And there was an assignment that Howard Hemmerbaum gave me to do who later on became my husband.

00:38:55.000 --> 00:38:58.000
We realized that people couldn't read or write.

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:09.000
So we got one of the churches to allow us to teach people how to read and write and specifically to learn how to sign their name.

00:39:09.000 --> 00:39:25.000
So when it came time to vote they could register, fill out that application because one of the things that came up was the white community was trying to force people to have to fill out application out,

00:39:25.000 --> 00:39:28.000
which is where that voter education application came from.

00:39:28.000 --> 00:39:35.000
So in order to do that you needed to know how to read and specifically you should at least know how to sign your name.

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:40.000
You could get somebody else to fill out application out for you, but you needed to sign your name.

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:42.000
So we got one of the churches.

00:39:42.000 --> 00:39:49.000
I think it was first Baptist church that let us use their basement.

00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:57.000
And a couple of the civil rights workers would work with them on reading and writing a couple of nights a week.

00:39:57.000 --> 00:40:11.000
And so things like that we had to change around because we get word that the white clan or whatever they call itself, not all of them would, you know, they wanted to fit into that name with just vigilantes.

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:18.000
They would wait till they got dark and try to come through them and bring physical harm to the different ones.

00:40:18.000 --> 00:40:24.000
Let me, this is, I want to spend even more time here talking about all this history and yet more detail.

00:40:24.000 --> 00:40:35.000
Can you, can you take me back to, I think the, as I have, as I've read and you can tell me this, this sounds right or not, that the, that the snake folks, and you've mentioned a few of them,

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:47.000
Howard Hemelbaum, Jim Jones, Bill Hansen, others, first came into Helena, Arkansas, and West Helena, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas, as I have it in the spring of 63 and the first demonstration sort of active protests in Helena, Arkansas.

00:40:47.000 --> 00:40:50.000
For November of 63.

00:40:50.000 --> 00:41:00.000
It may have been because I know I've spent a whole year after the voter registration because I didn't get out of high school to 66.

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:04.000
So I was reflecting back that that had to be before 64.

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:19.000
I know it was a guy named James Heel, Stanley Tillman, and I think Michael Simmons came with that group.

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:27.000
Some of those guys were one, one I was from Portland, one I was from Seattle, and Mike I think was from New York.

00:41:28.000 --> 00:41:43.000
But I remember Stanley Tillman was athlete, and he spent a lot of time getting to know me.

00:41:43.000 --> 00:41:53.000
I wonder about him sometimes now, but he asked me if I had, if it was any sports that I did, that I wanted to do that I had never been able to do it.

00:41:54.000 --> 00:42:08.000
I said, well, I always wanted to learn soccer, and a couple of times, at Eliza Miller High School, we tried to get a little soccer team going, but a lot of people didn't seem like they were interested in it.

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:15.000
And I said, I'd like the bowl, too, so we do y'all have a bowl in there, and I was like, you ever there on that black folks go there.

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:27.000
Because at that time when they came on the streets, you still had water fountains that had whites only on it, and signs on the bathrooms and stuff, whites only.

00:42:27.000 --> 00:42:36.000
If you were blessed enough to be able to drink water, use the bathroom in some places, it would have colored.

00:42:36.000 --> 00:42:43.000
And so Mr. Tillman came up with this idea of one day that he was going bowl.

00:42:45.000 --> 00:42:50.000
And I told my mom, Mr. Tillman's going to teach me how to bowl, mom.

00:42:50.000 --> 00:42:54.000
Is it okay if I go? She was like, yeah, you can go.

00:42:54.000 --> 00:42:57.000
So we went to the only bowl in that alley we had.

00:42:57.000 --> 00:43:02.000
It's between Helen and West Helen, that area is called Midland Heights.

00:43:02.000 --> 00:43:05.000
So we went in.

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:11.000
He knew all of the ins and outs of bowl, and so he went up to rent the shoes, they wouldn't rent them the shoes.

00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:14.000
He said, we need a lane.

00:43:14.000 --> 00:43:17.000
She's like, well, you can't bowl without shoes.

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:19.000
He said, yeah, sure we can.

00:43:19.000 --> 00:43:21.000
Are you going to let us have the lane or not?

00:43:21.000 --> 00:43:24.000
So she let us have the lane.

00:43:24.000 --> 00:43:26.000
We got over to the lane.

00:43:26.000 --> 00:43:28.000
He said, take the shoes off.

00:43:28.000 --> 00:43:31.000
We kept our socks on and we proceeded the bowl.

00:43:31.000 --> 00:43:36.000
I got to chance the bowl the whole game before the police showed up.

00:43:36.000 --> 00:43:39.000
This is before after the police showed up.

00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:42.000
Excuse me.

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:45.000
Ask your question again.

00:43:45.000 --> 00:43:49.000
Was this before or after the Civil Rights Act at pass?

00:43:49.000 --> 00:43:52.000
This is before the Civil Rights Act at pass.

00:43:52.000 --> 00:43:54.000
Yes.

00:43:54.000 --> 00:44:01.000
Mr. Tillman, I just wanted to ask, was Mr. Tillman white or black?

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:03.000
He was black.

00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:11.000
He was a big guy about six, three, probably way to 200 pounds.

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:16.000
He was a fairly attractive young man, pleasant guy.

00:44:16.000 --> 00:44:21.000
He wasn't threatening when you saw him.

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:32.000
When the police got there, they tried to intimidate me by asking me my name and who my parents were and stuff like that.

00:44:32.000 --> 00:44:36.000
I didn't have no fear for any being.

00:44:36.000 --> 00:44:38.000
Never did.

00:44:38.000 --> 00:44:40.000
And I said, why are you on my name?

00:44:40.000 --> 00:44:43.000
He said, who are your parents?

00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:46.000
And everybody knew my dad is bigum.

00:44:46.000 --> 00:44:50.000
But he was like six, one, weight about 180 pounds.

00:44:50.000 --> 00:44:52.000
His mom described him.

00:44:52.000 --> 00:44:55.000
He was tailimating.

00:44:55.000 --> 00:44:58.000
So he was like, oh, I know bigum.

00:44:58.000 --> 00:45:01.000
And he told me, oh, you out here, I said he does.

00:45:01.000 --> 00:45:05.000
Well, I don't think he know what you're doing.

00:45:05.000 --> 00:45:08.000
And he made us put on our shoes and leave.

00:45:08.000 --> 00:45:11.000
We didn't try to fight back and things.

00:45:11.000 --> 00:45:13.000
We just put on our shoes and left.

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:17.000
My first game ever in life, I bow 98.

00:45:17.000 --> 00:45:21.000
Were you surprised that you got...

00:45:21.000 --> 00:45:25.000
Actually, no, the surprise that they let you bow in the first place.

00:45:25.000 --> 00:45:28.000
But since they wouldn't let us have shoes.

00:45:28.000 --> 00:45:33.000
But Mr. Tillman, I guess, kind of shocked the lady that was waiting on us

00:45:33.000 --> 00:45:38.000
that she didn't know how to deny us the lane, even though she had denied us the shoes.

00:45:38.000 --> 00:45:40.000
So she let us have the lane.

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:43.000
And he was like, you know, real bold in a way.

00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:45.000
Did it came back to the first...

00:45:45.000 --> 00:45:49.000
How did you first hear about these young civil rights workers coming into the community?

00:45:49.000 --> 00:45:50.000
I don't remember.

00:45:50.000 --> 00:45:53.000
They just started popped up.

00:45:53.000 --> 00:45:55.000
And to some of the ladies, folks.

00:45:55.000 --> 00:46:00.000
For example, you just called him Mr. Tillman, but he wasn't that many years older than you were.

00:46:00.000 --> 00:46:04.000
Well, he was in college and he may have even graduated from college.

00:46:04.000 --> 00:46:05.000
I was still in high school.

00:46:05.000 --> 00:46:07.000
So these early 20s and you were 15-ish.

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:08.000
Yeah.

00:46:08.000 --> 00:46:09.000
Exactly.

00:46:09.000 --> 00:46:11.000
So I don't know.

00:46:11.000 --> 00:46:14.000
I guess just because they were bigger than me.

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:17.000
Well, that's a lot older.

00:46:17.000 --> 00:46:20.000
And of course, they didn't want me to call them Mr. either.

00:46:20.000 --> 00:46:23.000
But, you know, that was the train.

00:46:23.000 --> 00:46:27.000
People older than you, you know, you greeted them as Mr. and Mrs.

00:46:27.000 --> 00:46:30.000
But tell me about these folks and how you began to make sense of them

00:46:30.000 --> 00:46:34.000
because they're coming in to take on the civil rights fight.

00:46:34.000 --> 00:46:38.000
It's pretty difficult and dangerous work.

00:46:38.000 --> 00:46:41.000
So how did you begin to come to understand these people?

00:46:41.000 --> 00:46:46.000
Talking to them, we had meetings in their homes, you know,

00:46:46.000 --> 00:46:50.000
to explain what it was that we were trying to do.

00:46:50.000 --> 00:46:55.000
And I don't remember any of them even mentioning the Little Rock, Arkansas 9

00:46:55.000 --> 00:46:56.000
in our communication.

00:46:56.000 --> 00:47:01.000
They may have, it may have escaped me because I may have had this ton of vision

00:47:01.000 --> 00:47:08.000
about how I could solve my problem right then, West Helena, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas, you know.

00:47:08.000 --> 00:47:15.000
But we came to Little Rock, Arkansas within the first probably 12 months

00:47:15.000 --> 00:47:21.000
after they were there because I remember coming to a meeting in Ferndale, Arkansas,

00:47:21.000 --> 00:47:24.000
which is a little community west of here.

00:47:24.000 --> 00:47:33.000
It was a Presbyterian village and we went there and had like workshops every day for like two or three days.

00:47:33.000 --> 00:47:40.000
And there were quite a few people from my community that went because I know I had a cousin that was there.

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:44.000
There was like nine or ten years older than me.

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:47.000
And he was married as a matter of fact.

00:47:47.000 --> 00:47:52.000
And because we tried to get the whole community in there,

00:47:52.000 --> 00:48:00.000
but people weren't as stick-tuitive as I guess I was because I wanted to be in everything that was going on.

00:48:00.000 --> 00:48:02.000
I wanted to know what was going on.

00:48:02.000 --> 00:48:04.000
I was played out.

00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:12.000
I participated in, after I graduated from high school, we had different sit-ins

00:48:12.000 --> 00:48:16.000
and demonstrations here in Little Rock, Arkansas to open up the state capital.

00:48:16.000 --> 00:48:20.000
And people got pitched out on their faces, I mean, literally.

00:48:20.000 --> 00:48:21.000
How was the cafeteria?

00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:22.000
Yes.

00:48:22.000 --> 00:48:29.000
And they threw mustard gas bombs on us.

00:48:29.000 --> 00:48:39.000
You mentioned earlier that in the bowling alley incident that you didn't fear any man.

00:48:39.000 --> 00:48:41.000
Do you think it was just a part of...

00:48:41.000 --> 00:48:44.000
How did you come to be a person who didn't have fear in situations like that?

00:48:44.000 --> 00:48:45.000
Do you have a sense of that?

00:48:45.000 --> 00:48:47.000
I think it was probably...

00:48:47.000 --> 00:48:53.000
In Lexa, even though the separation was there,

00:48:53.000 --> 00:49:01.000
there was a certain like camaraderie between the blacks and whites that lived there.

00:49:01.000 --> 00:49:13.000
There was a support in times of crisis that it seemed like both sides of that track could come together.

00:49:13.000 --> 00:49:21.000
And like the musklinis, the way they treated people, they were just nice people.

00:49:21.000 --> 00:49:29.000
You know, Mr. Hometized, you had wanted to families that stuck out on both sides of the track that could say,

00:49:29.000 --> 00:49:31.000
no, I'm better than you.

00:49:31.000 --> 00:49:33.000
You know what I'm saying?

00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:39.000
But it was a rural, small community.

00:49:39.000 --> 00:49:49.000
Had our own post office, had our own railroads station, we had our own garage, we had our restaurants.

00:49:49.000 --> 00:49:51.000
We were like a self-sustaining place.

00:49:51.000 --> 00:49:56.000
And even if you went there now, you were like, this place got stuck in time.

00:49:56.000 --> 00:49:59.000
But some people are going back there to leave.

00:49:59.000 --> 00:50:02.000
What do you think the total population was?

00:50:02.000 --> 00:50:08.000
It probably was 2000 people, something like that.

00:50:08.000 --> 00:50:11.000
And the racial split would have been approximately...

00:50:11.000 --> 00:50:13.000
Maybe in about even.

00:50:13.000 --> 00:50:20.000
Yeah, because I think the county back in those days, the county overall was about 56, 57.

00:50:20.000 --> 00:50:21.000
Yeah.

00:50:21.000 --> 00:50:28.000
And why the move to a cell?

00:50:28.000 --> 00:50:37.000
Probably just my parents getting older, wasn't so much focused.

00:50:37.000 --> 00:50:43.000
And then we had two older children who were gone.

00:50:43.000 --> 00:50:49.000
One had died, one was... had just signed up to go to Vietnam.

00:50:49.000 --> 00:50:51.000
The oldest son.

00:50:51.000 --> 00:50:58.000
So then the next oldest daughter, she was a special needs child.

00:50:58.000 --> 00:51:03.000
And then the next oldest child was my sister who was a year older than me.

00:51:03.000 --> 00:51:06.000
So we were all kind of young.

00:51:06.000 --> 00:51:10.000
And I think that probably is what caused us to move to West Helena, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas.

00:51:10.000 --> 00:51:14.000
Because it was like more modernized.

00:51:14.000 --> 00:51:20.000
But even in West Helena, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas, we wind up going to the cotton field again.

00:51:20.000 --> 00:51:25.000
And that wasn't a very pleasant thing.

00:51:25.000 --> 00:51:29.000
I think, sure, left I got there.

00:51:29.000 --> 00:51:31.000
I was in the cotton field one day.

00:51:31.000 --> 00:51:38.000
We went on a bus to a place called Snow Lake, Arkansas, Arkansas, which is on the other side of Elaine.

00:51:38.000 --> 00:51:44.000
And five young men attempted to rape me.

00:51:44.000 --> 00:51:49.000
And the water boy happened to come through when they was hollering.

00:51:49.000 --> 00:51:51.000
Me, don't the house, me, don't the house.

00:51:51.000 --> 00:51:54.000
And it's one very muscular young man.

00:51:54.000 --> 00:51:56.000
And he was a football player.

00:51:56.000 --> 00:52:00.000
He stood up in my back with his knees.

00:52:00.000 --> 00:52:06.000
And of course, I suffered for the next 20 years.

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:12.000
So I finally had to have some surgery behind all that.

00:52:12.000 --> 00:52:16.000
And I was so mad.

00:52:16.000 --> 00:52:18.000
I wanted them dead.

00:52:18.000 --> 00:52:21.000
I wanted them locked up.

00:52:21.000 --> 00:52:23.000
And I know it was the Lord.

00:52:23.000 --> 00:52:26.000
Because when we got ready to leave that field,

00:52:26.000 --> 00:52:29.000
the bus got stuck.

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:34.000
When we was trying to get the bus out, the steering wheel came off the steering column.

00:52:34.000 --> 00:52:38.000
We didn't get out and died at about one or two o'clock in the morning.

00:52:38.000 --> 00:52:42.000
And when we passed the police station in West Hill,

00:52:42.000 --> 00:52:45.000
and I was going through because I wanted that bus driver to stop

00:52:45.000 --> 00:52:48.000
and let me go in there and turn their men.

00:52:48.000 --> 00:52:50.000
He wouldn't do it.

00:52:50.000 --> 00:52:52.000
So we went home.

00:52:52.000 --> 00:52:55.000
I told my mom about what had happened.

00:52:55.000 --> 00:52:59.000
And you could hear folks screaming and hollering all over the community

00:52:59.000 --> 00:53:02.000
because their parents was beating their parents.

00:53:02.000 --> 00:53:06.000
And I guess about two or three days later, my daddy came in the house.

00:53:06.000 --> 00:53:08.000
And I was laying down.

00:53:08.000 --> 00:53:10.000
I was hurting.

00:53:10.000 --> 00:53:12.000
He walked in and said,

00:53:12.000 --> 00:53:15.000
has my, he had a little name.

00:53:15.000 --> 00:53:20.000
He used to call a lot of his pets that I won't say on camera.

00:53:20.000 --> 00:53:22.000
He's like, has my little son, son, son.

00:53:22.000 --> 00:53:26.000
And I was like, I was just hollering my daddy to say,

00:53:26.000 --> 00:53:29.000
get my baby out of here and take her to the doctor.

00:53:29.000 --> 00:53:34.000
I didn't know what shape I was in until I was headed to the doctor.

00:53:34.000 --> 00:53:37.000
They had the ambulance come, getting me.

00:53:37.000 --> 00:53:42.000
And when that ambulance went across the railroad tracks, I almost died.

00:53:42.000 --> 00:53:47.000
And I was in the hospital for like three weeks behind that.

00:53:47.000 --> 00:53:49.000
So.

00:53:49.000 --> 00:53:52.000
This was after your move to West Hill.

00:53:52.000 --> 00:53:58.000
And there was another thing that helped me to want to just get out of there.

00:53:58.000 --> 00:54:00.000
You said these were five white teenagers.

00:54:00.000 --> 00:54:01.000
No, they weren't white.

00:54:01.000 --> 00:54:07.000
These were black guys who had gone out with the group to work in the fields.

00:54:07.000 --> 00:54:10.000
And so that hence that's when you said that we could,

00:54:10.000 --> 00:54:14.000
so the words spread that they had attempted this sense of the parents came after a conversation.

00:54:14.000 --> 00:54:16.000
Yeah.

00:54:16.000 --> 00:54:26.000
Can you, can you tell me a little bit about your impressions of Jim Jones,

00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:31.000
Hurricane Bomb, Jerry Casey?

00:54:31.000 --> 00:54:34.000
I looked up to all of those guys.

00:54:34.000 --> 00:54:39.000
They were like, Johnson.

00:54:39.000 --> 00:54:41.000
I guess now in the way I would describe them,

00:54:41.000 --> 00:54:46.000
they were all my Moses, you know.

00:54:46.000 --> 00:54:52.000
Someone who came to bring relief and liberty,

00:54:52.000 --> 00:54:59.000
to not only to me, but to the whole community.

00:54:59.000 --> 00:55:08.000
And it just seemed like the community didn't wrap themselves around these people enough.

00:55:08.000 --> 00:55:14.000
And I guess if I had got a sense of everybody being on board with them,

00:55:14.000 --> 00:55:17.000
I probably would have changed my whole attitude about wanting to leave.

00:55:17.000 --> 00:55:20.000
But after two and a half years, I didn't see that.

00:55:20.000 --> 00:55:23.000
So when it was my time to go, I left.

00:55:23.000 --> 00:55:26.000
And as a matter of fact, when I left,

00:55:26.000 --> 00:55:29.000
me and Howard Himmelbaum was secretly engaged,

00:55:29.000 --> 00:55:31.000
but I wasn't waiting on him.

00:55:31.000 --> 00:55:32.000
I said, I'm gone.

00:55:32.000 --> 00:55:37.000
If you want to marry me, you're going to come where I am.

00:55:37.000 --> 00:55:39.000
I sure did.

00:55:39.000 --> 00:55:41.000
I went to DC.

00:55:41.000 --> 00:55:46.000
And got employed two or three days after I got to DC

00:55:46.000 --> 00:55:51.000
with the Head Start program, went into training,

00:55:51.000 --> 00:55:55.000
and did very well.

00:55:55.000 --> 00:55:57.000
We'll come to that too.

00:55:57.000 --> 00:56:05.000
If you would, still some more details about the campaign and the West Helena, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas.

00:56:05.000 --> 00:56:12.000
You worked extensively on the effort to gather signatures to remove all the tax.

00:56:12.000 --> 00:56:14.000
And we were successful.

00:56:14.000 --> 00:56:15.000
How did that go?

00:56:15.000 --> 00:56:16.000
Can you describe that whole project?

00:56:16.000 --> 00:56:19.000
It was lonely.

00:56:19.000 --> 00:56:23.000
Because it was nobody ever to me, most of the time.

00:56:23.000 --> 00:56:28.000
I just sat on this one man's front porch of his business.

00:56:28.000 --> 00:56:32.000
I can't remember if I think it was Mr.

00:56:32.000 --> 00:56:36.000
I don't know what it was that means, man.

00:56:36.000 --> 00:56:40.000
Oh.

00:56:40.000 --> 00:56:42.000
I can't remember his name.

00:56:42.000 --> 00:56:45.000
I was going to boys.

00:56:45.000 --> 00:56:53.000
I sat on his storefront with a little table in front of him in the chair.

00:56:53.000 --> 00:56:58.000
The sheet that's all he had to do was put their name on the petition to abolish it.

00:56:58.000 --> 00:57:03.000
If they couldn't write their name, they'd put an X and I wrote their name for him.

00:57:03.000 --> 00:57:06.000
I guess I did that for two or three weeks.

00:57:06.000 --> 00:57:11.000
I'm like that until we felt like we had everybody's name on them.

00:57:11.000 --> 00:57:18.000
And doing that time was when Howard Himmelbaum proposed to me.

00:57:18.000 --> 00:57:24.000
Do you want to talk about how I'd be very interested if your couple were doing it?

00:57:24.000 --> 00:57:30.000
Talking about building this relationship with a young white man in West Helena, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas in the...

00:57:30.000 --> 00:57:33.000
He was very secretive.

00:57:33.000 --> 00:57:35.000
It was secretive to us.

00:57:35.000 --> 00:57:36.000
Let me put it like that.

00:57:36.000 --> 00:57:39.000
But it wasn't such a secret to most people that was around us.

00:57:39.000 --> 00:57:43.000
Because when two people care for each other, everybody knows it.

00:57:43.000 --> 00:57:48.000
You think you hide it, but you're not hiding it.

00:57:48.000 --> 00:57:59.000
As far as in the black community was concerned, maybe one or two people was concerned about it from the black community.

00:57:59.000 --> 00:58:07.000
There was a couple of young men that had tried to talk to me before Howard came on the scene.

00:58:07.000 --> 00:58:14.000
And what I've made to statement said, so you're going to take a white man over a black man?

00:58:14.000 --> 00:58:18.000
I said, I haven't taken any man.

00:58:18.000 --> 00:58:21.000
And we just left it at that.

00:58:21.000 --> 00:58:27.000
Then I had an older guy who was one of my dad's friends, or supposed to be one of my dad's friends.

00:58:27.000 --> 00:58:33.000
He saw me going to church when Sonny Moore and decided to make a derogatory statement to me.

00:58:33.000 --> 00:58:38.000
And when I got back home, he was sitting on my front porch talking to my daddy.

00:58:38.000 --> 00:58:45.000
So I just stopped right there and told my daddy what Mr. Ernest said to me when I was on my way to church.

00:58:45.000 --> 00:58:49.000
And he got the threat of his life that day.

00:58:49.000 --> 00:58:50.000
But...

00:58:50.000 --> 00:58:55.000
How'd your parents weigh that circumstance?

00:58:55.000 --> 00:58:57.000
My relationship with Howard.

00:58:57.000 --> 00:59:00.000
My mom loved Howard.

00:59:00.000 --> 00:59:09.000
My dad probably did too, but you know how you dads have your eyes way of expressing your feelings and sentiments and everything.

00:59:09.000 --> 00:59:11.000
My dad was afraid for me.

00:59:11.000 --> 00:59:20.000
That was really the bottom line when I asked him later on, you know, how did he really feel about me being in the civil rights movement and everything.

00:59:20.000 --> 00:59:21.000
He was afraid.

00:59:21.000 --> 00:59:24.000
He was afraid that his daughter was going to get hurt.

00:59:24.000 --> 00:59:28.000
Well, he was very afraid.

00:59:28.000 --> 00:59:33.000
He said it's for Howard. He liked Howard.

00:59:33.000 --> 00:59:40.000
He said he didn't feel like he would have treated him any differently than a black man.

00:59:40.000 --> 00:59:47.000
But my mom, she made sure that Howard knew how she felt about it.

00:59:47.000 --> 00:59:52.000
She thought we was married before we got married. She did tell me that later on.

00:59:52.000 --> 00:59:57.000
When I invited her to come to my wedding, she was like, I thought y'all's already married.

00:59:57.000 --> 01:00:02.000
But we weren't, you know, we just worked close together and everything.

01:00:02.000 --> 01:00:10.000
We went on different trips as we had marches and things like that to go to.

01:00:10.000 --> 01:00:14.000
I'm trying to remember if he was in Memphis when Martin Luther King got killed.

01:00:14.000 --> 01:00:18.000
But I know Myrtle Glasgow and I was there together.

01:00:18.000 --> 01:00:23.000
We shared rooms with Stokely Carmichael.

01:00:23.000 --> 01:00:28.000
I was just cleavering a couple of other guys that was there.

01:00:28.000 --> 01:00:38.000
Howard may have been somewhere else because there was a whole bunch of different type of activities and marches and things that was going on during that time.

01:00:38.000 --> 01:00:41.000
Go ahead.

01:00:41.000 --> 01:00:47.000
Going back to the full text since there were four white people that probably affected them as well.

01:00:47.000 --> 01:00:51.000
Were you also getting the assignment to show them the next couple of things?

01:00:51.000 --> 01:01:07.000
It was just a focus on the West tellin' the community, that segment that was covered like a community called New Edition, then West tellin' it's self.

01:01:07.000 --> 01:01:12.000
And see, the thing you have to understand about poll tax to mine the standing.

01:01:12.000 --> 01:01:15.000
White folks didn't have to pay poll tax.

01:01:15.000 --> 01:01:22.000
Right. It was meant to hinder the blacks from being able to vote.

01:01:22.000 --> 01:01:27.000
It wasn't about that one way it was about.

01:01:27.000 --> 01:01:31.000
We never arrested anyone.

01:01:31.000 --> 01:01:34.000
Before you moved away.

01:01:34.000 --> 01:01:40.000
I would arrest one time I was because I was hungry.

01:01:40.000 --> 01:01:43.000
Excuse me.

01:01:44.000 --> 01:01:47.000
Okay, we're back after a short break.

01:01:47.000 --> 01:01:50.000
Let me ask.

01:01:50.000 --> 01:01:54.000
Were you about to talk about arrests?

01:01:54.000 --> 01:01:55.000
Oh yeah.

01:01:55.000 --> 01:01:58.000
One time I was down home.

01:01:58.000 --> 01:02:02.000
It was after I had left and I was married at the time.

01:02:02.000 --> 01:02:08.000
And of course, you know, the struggle continued on for a bunch of years and still do.

01:02:08.000 --> 01:02:19.000
But actually active as part of SNCC and then a group that we created here in Little Rock, Arkansas called the Black United Youth.

01:02:19.000 --> 01:02:27.000
We would still go to West tellin' the Earl, Blackville (?), McGehee.

01:02:27.000 --> 01:02:39.000
Wherever there was an unrest and still the Jim Crow Law, you know, being enforced against our people.

01:02:39.000 --> 01:02:46.000
We went down to West tellin' the one summer to work the whole summer. That was the idea.

01:02:46.000 --> 01:02:52.000
So after we had been down there, I guess about three, four days, we didn't have any money.

01:02:52.000 --> 01:02:56.000
And we were hungry, we were tired, we were hot, you know.

01:02:56.000 --> 01:03:00.000
And even though my parents lived there, you know, my parents were very poor.

01:03:00.000 --> 01:03:03.000
We'd been poor all of my life.

01:03:03.000 --> 01:03:06.000
I said, well, let's just go ask them for something to eat.

01:03:06.000 --> 01:03:08.000
So we went into a grocery store.

01:03:08.000 --> 01:03:12.000
I think it was a big star.

01:03:12.000 --> 01:03:19.000
We went into the grocery store and I asked for the manager, told him who we were, what we were doing.

01:03:19.000 --> 01:03:24.000
And we was just hungry, we was wanting to give us some meat and bread, you know.

01:03:24.000 --> 01:03:29.000
They wouldn't give us anything. They had this whole store full of food, you know.

01:03:29.000 --> 01:03:36.000
And I said, well, I think I'll just give me some bread and meat.

01:03:36.000 --> 01:03:38.000
And that's what we did.

01:03:38.000 --> 01:03:43.000
And the call of police on us took us to jail.

01:03:43.000 --> 01:03:47.000
And I got to jail and they found out who I was. They wouldn't got my daddy.

01:03:47.000 --> 01:03:50.000
Brought him back up there.

01:03:50.000 --> 01:03:53.000
I said, girl, what are you doing?

01:03:53.000 --> 01:03:57.000
You get picked up for stealing food. I said, dad, I did not steal the food.

01:03:57.000 --> 01:04:00.000
I went in there and I asked for it and they wouldn't give it to me.

01:04:00.000 --> 01:04:03.000
So I just took what I needed to eat. That was it.

01:04:03.000 --> 01:04:06.000
I didn't try to hide it, you know.

01:04:06.000 --> 01:04:12.000
Of course, they let us go because they knew my dad and they knew my upbringing and everything.

01:04:12.000 --> 01:04:15.000
He said, I don't know what I'm going to do with you.

01:04:15.000 --> 01:04:18.000
Was that a black or a controlled store?

01:04:18.000 --> 01:04:23.000
It was a food change, you know.

01:04:23.000 --> 01:04:32.000
And the police officer said, you better be glad people know your dad.

01:04:32.000 --> 01:04:38.000
But I said, you know, we all grown up to believe that when you need some, you ask people for it.

01:04:38.000 --> 01:04:42.000
And they have it to give. Then they should share it with you.

01:04:42.000 --> 01:04:47.000
I said, you out and do that. I said, you taught me that, but that's not what you're doing.

01:04:47.000 --> 01:04:55.000
Let me ask about the wider SNCC effort in the Delta in those years.

01:04:55.000 --> 01:05:01.000
Did you have, did you go with SNCC folks in places like Golden Forest City for demonstrations?

01:05:01.000 --> 01:05:05.000
Or did you pretty much in the high school years where you sticking around West Helena, Arkansas?

01:05:05.000 --> 01:05:13.000
I stuck around West Helena, Arkansas and the good work long was in Gould, Arkansas, Arkansas and I think it was Laura Foner.

01:05:13.000 --> 01:05:24.000
They were both in good area. We had people in good, we had people in Little Rock, Arkansas, Arkansas, people in West Helena, Arkansas, people in Pine Bluff, Arkansas.

01:05:24.000 --> 01:05:30.000
But that was later for a city came like after I was out of high school.

01:05:30.000 --> 01:05:35.000
I think they had tried to go into for a city a couple of times.

01:05:35.000 --> 01:05:41.000
And I think the very first time they went through there was a terrible shootout.

01:05:41.000 --> 01:05:47.000
And I think that's why people kind of backed off, you know.

01:05:47.000 --> 01:05:58.000
Even in the difference between Helena, Arkansas and West Helena, Arkansas was in such contrast that the young man James Heal that I was telling you about.

01:05:58.000 --> 01:06:07.000
He went to Helena, Arkansas to do some work and they arrested him and the judge would everybody sitting in the court threatened him by saying.

01:06:07.000 --> 01:06:14.000
Because he was 21 years old. He already had a master's degree. I believe in engineering. He said, Nigger.

01:06:14.000 --> 01:06:26.000
If you're smart enough to have a master's degree at 21 you ought to be a smart enough Nigger to get the hell out of Helena, Arkansas before you find yourself floating up like Nm. Heal.

01:06:26.000 --> 01:06:33.000
That's what he said, Torn. There was Judge Hester.

01:06:33.000 --> 01:06:38.000
And that young man left right after that too.

01:06:38.000 --> 01:06:50.000
Did you? You mentioned that one occasion when you were coming up when your father and other men in the black community set out of guard and armed guard to protect that young man.

01:06:50.000 --> 01:07:03.000
Did your father and other men in West Helena, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas, did they have to step forward or organize themselves in that way to provide some protection to black people in any West Helena, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas?

01:07:03.000 --> 01:07:20.000
They probably did but we didn't know about it. If things came up, there's this group called the Masons, which is basically the Masonic large disin and community.

01:07:20.000 --> 01:07:31.000
And I think that's the force that comes together. And there's not a whole bunch of mouthwork that goes on. People just come together and take action and do what need to be done.

01:07:31.000 --> 01:07:50.000
Let me ask you two about when when Snick arrived in Helena, Arkansas, you had mentioned earlier that it would be a mistake to think about the black community always in these instances as being perfectly unified in their opinions because there's a lot of different perspective.

01:07:50.000 --> 01:08:02.000
So I'm curious about your recollections about how different parts of the black community reacted to the right or Snick because some people welcomed them and some people didn't.

01:08:02.000 --> 01:08:06.000
And some just ignored them like they didn't exist.

01:08:06.000 --> 01:08:10.000
About the pastors, what was their actions in?

01:08:10.000 --> 01:08:31.000
Some of the pastors received them. A lot of the churches in West Helena, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas, the pastors didn't even live there. They lived in Memphis or they lived in Mississippi and they drove in on Friday or Saturday.

01:08:31.000 --> 01:08:46.000
So they had a great escape, so to speak. It was the deacons and the mothers of the church that more or less you had to deal with to get into the church itself.

01:08:46.000 --> 01:08:52.000
Who helped the Snick folks find a freedom house?

01:08:52.000 --> 01:08:59.000
They never had a freedom house in Helena, Arkansas. They had one in West Helena, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas.

01:08:59.000 --> 01:09:11.000
And then we had, I think we had two or three because murder, eventually, like set up her own personal home there.

01:09:11.000 --> 01:09:16.000
And then the guys had a house and the young women had a house.

01:09:16.000 --> 01:09:25.000
But most of the young women, we would try to set them up in homes where there was a father and a mother, secure living situation.

01:09:25.000 --> 01:09:31.000
Because when murder first came, she actually lived in the house with us.

01:09:31.000 --> 01:09:42.000
And that's the thing that impacted her so much about my family, the love that she experienced there, even in our poverty, stricken state.

01:09:42.000 --> 01:09:51.000
She was just amazed how we could open up our arms and our home and everything and receive a total stranger into our home.

01:09:52.000 --> 01:09:56.000
But that was the way my parents were.

01:09:56.000 --> 01:10:01.000
I lost the uncle because our family just believed in helping people.

01:10:01.000 --> 01:10:10.000
And he allowed a hobo, we call him hobos then, not homeless people, but because you didn't stay in that state.

01:10:10.000 --> 01:10:15.000
The idea is that you would recoup.

01:10:15.000 --> 01:10:30.000
So you help a man along the way until he could get back on his feet and this man woke up in the middle of the night and split my uncle's head with an axe and an axe bounced off of his head to his wife's head to his one of his children's head.

01:10:30.000 --> 01:10:33.000
Because he was the only one that actually died.

01:10:33.000 --> 01:10:38.000
But he'd never stopped my family from extending a helping hand to people.

01:10:38.000 --> 01:10:43.000
Can you tell us about Mertel and her live on her?

01:10:43.000 --> 01:10:50.000
She came to work in the summer program with SNCC.

01:10:50.000 --> 01:11:01.000
She must have been 64. She came out Oakland, California in Little Old Boo got never seen a Volkswagen before in my life.

01:11:01.000 --> 01:11:06.000
And of course Mertel was when we saw she was a white woman.

01:11:06.000 --> 01:11:14.000
But she was actually a black woman. Her hair was long and curly, you know.

01:11:14.000 --> 01:11:24.000
You're very fair. And we were just fascinated with the little bitty car.

01:11:24.000 --> 01:11:29.000
She decided she wanted to stay but she needed a place to stay.

01:11:29.000 --> 01:11:33.000
Me and her just, I guess we hit it off immediately.

01:11:33.000 --> 01:11:40.000
She became my big sister that I had lost like a year or two before she showed up.

01:11:40.000 --> 01:11:49.000
And she wound up staying with us and we got close and close.

01:11:49.000 --> 01:11:53.000
Eventually, you know, she moved out of us. I guess she got comfortable in the community.

01:11:53.000 --> 01:11:57.000
She rented her a little house up the street from us.

01:11:57.000 --> 01:12:01.000
And I could go to them and visit her and help her to cook and stuff like that.

01:12:01.000 --> 01:12:04.000
She was kind of a vegetarian all of her life.

01:12:04.000 --> 01:12:09.000
So she was in the right community to get all the vegetables she wanted.

01:12:09.000 --> 01:12:14.000
But when she'd go somewhere, I would get her to ask mom to let me go with her.

01:12:14.000 --> 01:12:18.000
That's how I got to travel. Because it was just me and the guys I wouldn't went.

01:12:18.000 --> 01:12:23.000
You know? No, that's my daughter. And then after a while after my mom,

01:12:23.000 --> 01:12:25.000
then we got to know them real good.

01:12:25.000 --> 01:12:28.000
She said, y'all better protect my baby now.

01:12:28.000 --> 01:12:30.000
You look after her. That's my baby.

01:12:30.000 --> 01:12:33.000
So because of your experience in the whole movement,

01:12:33.000 --> 01:12:35.000
change quite a little, something.

01:12:35.000 --> 01:12:42.000
It did. I got a chance to go to Atlanta to different marches and things

01:12:42.000 --> 01:12:53.000
that was going on there fighting against people being refused to entrance into colleges,

01:12:53.000 --> 01:12:56.000
universities and stuff like that.

01:12:56.000 --> 01:12:59.000
I think I spent about a week over there one year.

01:12:59.000 --> 01:13:05.000
I was like, I'd never seen anything like it in my life.

01:13:05.000 --> 01:13:11.000
I don't know who this, it may have been the president of one of the black colleges over there

01:13:11.000 --> 01:13:15.000
that we spent like three or four days in their home.

01:13:15.000 --> 01:13:20.000
But it was like constant meetings and planning and strategizing.

01:13:20.000 --> 01:13:22.000
It was interesting.

01:13:22.000 --> 01:13:24.000
This is what I was still in the last time.

01:13:24.000 --> 01:13:26.000
Yeah, it was before I moved.

01:13:26.000 --> 01:13:28.000
Those meetings you were just traveling around Atlanta?

01:13:28.000 --> 01:13:29.000
Yes.

01:13:29.000 --> 01:13:34.000
Did you have a sense in these years of the tensions that were emerging in SNCC?

01:13:34.000 --> 01:13:37.000
Obviously, I'm sure you did.

01:13:37.000 --> 01:13:40.000
And I feel like I'm sitting in Bremen.

01:13:40.000 --> 01:13:41.000
Is it Greenwich?

01:13:41.000 --> 01:13:47.000
Greenwicher are trying to leave SNCC's Arkansas program forward.

01:13:47.000 --> 01:13:55.000
Yeah, I heard a little conversation's going on.

01:13:55.000 --> 01:14:04.000
I guess I didn't enter into any of it because I just felt like it was something that would pass.

01:14:04.000 --> 01:14:10.000
Everybody was in the back in the struggle for the same reason.

01:14:10.000 --> 01:14:13.000
You're going to have little squabbles like little children.

01:14:13.000 --> 01:14:21.000
You fight this hour and the next hour you're okay.

01:14:21.000 --> 01:14:27.000
And then sometimes when you're dealing with pastors too, they have another way of looking at stuff

01:14:27.000 --> 01:14:33.000
that you have to learn how to get past.

01:14:33.000 --> 01:14:36.000
And Bill, he was like a...

01:14:36.000 --> 01:14:40.000
He'd say what he had to say and then he would just go on off.

01:14:40.000 --> 01:14:43.000
Bill hasn't.

01:14:43.000 --> 01:14:45.000
And he had his own family.

01:14:45.000 --> 01:14:51.000
So he had his privacy that he had somewhere to go and just block everything else out.

01:14:51.000 --> 01:14:56.000
So you never knew unless you were with him what was going on.

01:14:56.000 --> 01:14:59.000
And it's hard and the same thing with Rev. Ben Grinage.

01:14:59.000 --> 01:15:00.000
Bill hasn't had married.

01:15:00.000 --> 01:15:01.000
You're the busier tonight.

01:15:01.000 --> 01:15:03.000
So they were married by the time you were there.

01:15:03.000 --> 01:15:04.000
They were married when I met them.

01:15:04.000 --> 01:15:07.000
Yeah.

01:15:07.000 --> 01:15:12.000
Yeah.

01:15:12.000 --> 01:15:20.000
And some people, you know, in my heart, I guess I just knew they weren't going to stay around long because

01:15:20.000 --> 01:15:24.000
it was sort of like with Jim Hill when he got threatened and he left.

01:15:24.000 --> 01:15:28.000
You know, I could appreciate him leaving that and wanting to leave.

01:15:28.000 --> 01:15:30.000
But I could appreciate him leaving.

01:15:30.000 --> 01:15:36.000
There was his life and he had to do what he thought was best for himself.

01:15:36.000 --> 01:15:39.000
But everybody has a family.

01:15:39.000 --> 01:15:40.000
They had somewhere to go.

01:15:40.000 --> 01:15:47.000
If they didn't come to live, they came to see what they could do to help and change things in our community.

01:15:47.000 --> 01:15:51.000
And there were some effective changes.

01:15:51.000 --> 01:16:00.000
When I graduated from high school and went to DC, I spent what, six months.

01:16:00.000 --> 01:16:02.000
I actually I spent almost a year there.

01:16:02.000 --> 01:16:11.000
I did spend a year there because I didn't get married to a March of 67.

01:16:11.000 --> 01:16:22.000
It was getting married and continually living in the struggle.

01:16:22.000 --> 01:16:28.000
Being cautious not to walk down the street, holding hands and stuff like that.

01:16:28.000 --> 01:16:34.000
That was really when it became alive to me after we got married.

01:16:34.000 --> 01:16:42.000
I'm like, you know what, if I can't be myself, I may as well not be living in this world.

01:16:42.000 --> 01:16:46.000
So people just had to deal with who I was and who I was married to.

01:16:46.000 --> 01:16:50.000
And if they wanted to be ugly, that was okay.

01:16:50.000 --> 01:16:53.000
You know, if I felt like I needed to respond to it, I did.

01:16:53.000 --> 01:16:57.000
If I didn't need to respond to it, I didn't.

01:16:58.000 --> 01:17:05.000
So, and after a while, I mean, we had enough friends that we could socialize with

01:17:05.000 --> 01:17:11.000
that running into the negativity of some periodically, it really didn't bother.

01:17:11.000 --> 01:17:14.000
It didn't bother me. I don't think it bothered Howard.

01:17:14.000 --> 01:17:20.000
I don't because in the Black and White community, we developed a lot of friends.

01:17:20.000 --> 01:17:21.000
We did.

01:17:22.000 --> 01:17:29.000
After one last question, then we'll move on to past 66 and reach some of those, some of that history.

01:17:29.000 --> 01:17:36.000
How did you balance all your involvement in the movement with getting finished through high school?

01:17:36.000 --> 01:17:38.000
Was there a lot of...

01:17:38.000 --> 01:17:43.000
Just participating in things that was going on in the community at night,

01:17:43.000 --> 01:17:48.000
staying on track with school during the day, you know.

01:17:48.000 --> 01:17:54.000
If there were activities outside of the community, usually it was on the weekend.

01:17:54.000 --> 01:18:01.000
If it was something during the week, then I just didn't participate in it, you know.

01:18:01.000 --> 01:18:07.000
And I guess in my last three months or so of high school,

01:18:08.000 --> 01:18:12.000
I don't know if we did that much traveling.

01:18:12.000 --> 01:18:19.000
We may have, I know it's always something going on in the community, you know.

01:18:20.000 --> 01:18:23.000
Every night and then, somebody would get threatened.

01:18:23.000 --> 01:18:26.000
We have to deal with that.

01:18:26.000 --> 01:18:28.000
Stand guard.

01:18:28.000 --> 01:18:29.000
We could...

01:18:29.000 --> 01:18:35.000
With Jerry Kasey being on the team and being one of the young men from the community,

01:18:35.000 --> 01:18:45.000
he had friends and family that he could call upon to help give oversight and protection and security around one of the freedom houses.

01:18:45.000 --> 01:18:46.000
That was...

01:18:46.000 --> 01:18:47.000
It was just one house.

01:18:47.000 --> 01:18:49.000
They just two or three times.

01:18:49.000 --> 01:18:50.000
I know they tried...

01:18:50.000 --> 01:18:51.000
They shot into it once.

01:18:51.000 --> 01:18:57.000
They threw a couple of modest off-cocktails at it a couple of different times.

01:18:57.000 --> 01:19:03.000
And because they were nearby, I think after a while they realized that people were looking, you know,

01:19:03.000 --> 01:19:08.000
back in these places where the guys were living and everything and they begged out.

01:19:08.000 --> 01:19:10.000
But it's...

01:19:10.000 --> 01:19:15.000
Like Michael Simmons, I know he was one, he didn't make no bones about it.

01:19:15.000 --> 01:19:18.000
He said, man, I'm not down up in here for nobody, you know.

01:19:18.000 --> 01:19:20.000
You know Michael.

01:19:20.000 --> 01:19:25.000
But he was just a down-to-earth type person.

01:19:25.000 --> 01:19:29.000
So I think he stayed like one summer and then he left.

01:19:29.000 --> 01:19:39.000
Well, that recollection brings to mind, of course, the whole tension inside SNCC, especially in these years, 64, 65, 66.

01:19:39.000 --> 01:19:44.000
The whole... the questioning about the whole theory and practice of non-violence and it's that.

01:19:44.000 --> 01:19:50.000
Yeah, I remember that because of...

01:19:50.000 --> 01:19:53.000
I'll decide to help Martin Luther King.

01:19:53.000 --> 01:19:58.000
And Martin positioned us to get killed all the time.

01:19:58.000 --> 01:20:02.000
You know, his activities positioned people to get killed.

01:20:02.000 --> 01:20:05.000
There's no question about it.

01:20:05.000 --> 01:20:10.000
And SNCC's focus was non-violence.

01:20:10.000 --> 01:20:19.000
And of course, H.R. Brown and the Black Panther Party came out of that because some people were saying, I'm picking up my gun.

01:20:19.000 --> 01:20:24.000
You know, this killing of blacks got to stop.

01:20:24.000 --> 01:20:29.000
And so the Black Panther movement came out of that.

01:20:29.000 --> 01:20:31.000
What was it?

01:20:31.000 --> 01:20:45.000
The (Cornell) Black Liberation Front came out of it with the students coming out of Cornell University with the gun, strapped around them and stuff, which one of those young men was from Little Rock, Arkansas, it would feel.

01:20:45.000 --> 01:20:48.000
You probably know him, don't you?

01:20:48.000 --> 01:20:51.000
I think he lives in Chapel Hill, doesn't he?

01:20:51.000 --> 01:20:53.000
What was this for?

01:20:53.000 --> 01:20:58.000
Oh, I do actually know that.

01:20:58.000 --> 01:21:07.000
You see, it was Ed Laredixon.

01:21:07.000 --> 01:21:14.000
And Eric's somebody, I don't know what Eric's last name was, but it was the three young men that was on the front of that paper.

01:21:14.000 --> 01:21:19.000
They all came, the two of them came home with Ed when he came.

01:21:19.000 --> 01:21:24.000
And I think they may have stayed here year or two before they actually left.

01:21:24.000 --> 01:21:35.000
And when they left, Ed Laredixon came to North Carolina to further his education and actually got married and lived there for several years.

01:21:35.000 --> 01:21:39.000
It may still be there.

01:21:40.000 --> 01:21:48.000
But those, I guess there was part of the reason why I was in Memphis when Martin Luther King got killed.

01:21:48.000 --> 01:21:50.000
Yeah, can you tell me about it?

01:21:50.000 --> 01:21:53.000
From 66 through 68 and then we'll even go beyond that.

01:21:53.000 --> 01:21:57.000
So you left in May of 66 to Washington.

01:21:57.000 --> 01:22:05.000
Right. And stayed up there until actually that Christmas of 66.

01:22:06.000 --> 01:22:19.000
And right after Christmas I came to Little Rock, Arkansas and me and Howard planned our wedding and went to New York and March, got married, stayed up there for six weeks.

01:22:19.000 --> 01:22:24.000
Then after that just came back and kind of.

01:22:24.000 --> 01:22:49.000
I was going to school to become a key punch operator with Opportunities Industrialization Center, which was the Opportunities Industrialization Center that was a new organization to the South anyway to try and help blacks acquire vocational skills where they could get into the job market and make a decent living.

01:22:49.000 --> 01:22:55.000
So I got in that class so I could get me a skill and go to work.

01:22:55.000 --> 01:23:04.000
And of course I became a.

01:23:04.000 --> 01:23:06.000
Trying to look for the name for it.

01:23:06.000 --> 01:23:16.000
I was suing people left and right for not hiring me and I knew I was qualified and I was passing the test to get the jobs and stuff.

01:23:16.000 --> 01:23:28.000
I won a couple of major lawsuits in Pulaski County for class and I just because I was black but because of women and blacks.

01:23:28.000 --> 01:23:29.000
Class action.

01:23:29.000 --> 01:23:32.000
And plus county just for the record that's here.

01:23:32.000 --> 01:23:33.000
He's bright.

01:23:33.000 --> 01:23:41.000
And one of those companies was AMF Inc Inc and the other one was National Old Line Life Insurance Company.

01:23:41.000 --> 01:23:48.000
And AMF Inc actually left Arkansas and went to Israel after leaving open up their company over there.

01:23:48.000 --> 01:23:53.000
I found it out in the last couple of years.

01:23:53.000 --> 01:24:09.000
And National Online was I mean that was a major major when for women and blacks because they had a lot of women working for them.

01:24:09.000 --> 01:24:14.000
What did you think of filing the suits in 1967?

01:24:14.000 --> 01:24:15.000
Well since I was up there.

01:24:15.000 --> 01:24:17.000
It's just up here and how we came back here.

01:24:17.000 --> 01:24:18.000
Right.

01:24:18.000 --> 01:24:26.000
I graduated from Opportunities Industrialization Center that same year I believe was.

01:24:26.000 --> 01:24:39.000
And I got a job with the State Capitol as the first black office work in the administration office through much toll.

01:24:39.000 --> 01:24:43.000
Well because prior to that there was the whole episode of...

01:24:43.000 --> 01:24:51.000
I'm not even able to eat there and the cafeteria was still closed and everything.

01:24:51.000 --> 01:24:59.000
When I started to work there though I was I was hired to work in the Motor Vehicle Department.

01:24:59.000 --> 01:25:03.000
Very tough area to work in.

01:25:03.000 --> 01:25:16.000
You know when you go and purchase a vehicle and you had it at that time it was a three-part paper that was like four by five or something like that.

01:25:16.000 --> 01:25:24.000
And every one of those pieces of paper had a different hand right now because the individual was the one that filled it out.

01:25:24.000 --> 01:25:34.000
We were allowed three mistakes per batch and then each batch was in a way from 300 to 500 pieces of paper.

01:25:34.000 --> 01:25:46.000
Well Miss Carrie Hommebaum was up to the task but my director just didn't want me there.

01:25:46.000 --> 01:25:54.000
And God had positioned in the computer environment a young man that we were friends of his family.

01:25:54.000 --> 01:26:00.000
In the very first name my husband picked me up they took his detags off the vehicle and ran check.

01:26:00.000 --> 01:26:04.000
I found out I was married to this white guy.

01:26:04.000 --> 01:26:09.000
And I guess at that point this man just determined he was going to get rid of me.

01:26:09.000 --> 01:26:17.000
So after my 90 day period he told my supervisor to get rid of me and he didn't care how she did it.

01:26:17.000 --> 01:26:19.000
Just do it.

01:26:19.000 --> 01:26:29.000
So she was very sympathetic and her dismissing me she told me that if I needed a reference she'd be more than glad to give me a reference.

01:26:29.000 --> 01:26:34.000
She said but Mr. Luzano wants you out of here.

01:26:35.000 --> 01:26:37.000
So okay I didn't part.

01:26:37.000 --> 01:26:42.000
I said I'll take the reference letter.

01:26:42.000 --> 01:26:47.000
And of course I went home and told my husband what had happened so we went to John W. Walker W. Walker.

01:26:47.000 --> 01:26:52.000
I turned to John W. Walker W. Walker and told him what had happened.

01:26:52.000 --> 01:26:57.000
We worked up all of the details and we didn't even get the court on that one.

01:26:57.000 --> 01:27:03.000
We just went straight to (Winthrop) Rockefeller and gave him all the paperwork and he said,

01:27:03.000 --> 01:27:07.000
he's been working on paperwork and he's set up a meeting and everything.

01:27:07.000 --> 01:27:14.000
So he I'm going up in there to conference room for the governor.

01:27:14.000 --> 01:27:16.000
Great big go everything.

01:27:16.000 --> 01:27:21.000
Never been an office this big big table big chairs you know.

01:27:21.000 --> 01:27:25.000
And my name on every folder.

01:27:25.000 --> 01:27:30.000
So I'm just then observing everything.

01:27:30.000 --> 01:27:36.000
Director Luzano comes in the room to see my name on the folder and pick it up.

01:27:36.000 --> 01:27:39.000
When I get rid of somebody I don't know about a high back.

01:27:39.000 --> 01:27:43.000
And by that time (Winthrop) Rockefeller came in and he said,

01:27:43.000 --> 01:27:50.000
well you can just go to your office and get your things in leave because you won't be working here anymore.

01:27:50.000 --> 01:27:54.000
So Governor just fired the head of the department about the report.

01:27:54.000 --> 01:28:02.000
And it's interesting thing about I wonder what you thought about Rockefeller because he's that curious case.

01:28:02.000 --> 01:28:07.000
He's the first Republican governor elected in Arkansas during this session.

01:28:07.000 --> 01:28:12.000
And it was because partly because of all the paperwork and that we did.

01:28:12.000 --> 01:28:13.000
Exactly.

01:28:13.000 --> 01:28:27.000
And it was I think a lot of it was because of the human resource council that is the Elijah Coleman was the head of at the time.

01:28:27.000 --> 01:28:32.000
And another young woman his secretary Barbara Grace she was white.

01:28:32.000 --> 01:28:37.000
And I think Barbara may have even been from Stuttgart, Arkansas.

01:28:37.000 --> 01:28:47.000
So you know people on the team came from all different directions of Arkansas.

01:28:47.000 --> 01:28:53.000
Different races, different ideas, but all with a forward vision.

01:28:53.000 --> 01:28:58.000
What's your husband working for the Arkansas Council on Human Relations?

01:28:58.000 --> 01:29:03.000
I don't know if he was with them or if he was with the Urban League.

01:29:03.000 --> 01:29:12.000
I think he did some I think he did like some freelance work for the Arkansas Council on Human Relations.

01:29:12.000 --> 01:29:20.000
Because you know people believe it and I think some of the people was like well I don't know we should hire a white man to work for us.

01:29:20.000 --> 01:29:27.000
You know they didn't just come out and say it but they didn't want to see a stop and okay.

01:29:27.000 --> 01:29:35.000
So he did a little freelance stuff and he finally landed a position with Urban League.

01:29:35.000 --> 01:29:37.000
The moment that had it up to human relations.

01:29:37.000 --> 01:29:39.000
Right.

01:29:39.000 --> 01:29:47.000
And see how it had his way of dealing with things that I think he threatened some people.

01:29:47.000 --> 01:29:50.000
And I think Mr. Coleman was one of those people.

01:29:50.000 --> 01:30:00.000
He liked him but he wasn't sure he wanted him around.

01:30:00.000 --> 01:30:02.000
I lost my thought.

01:30:02.000 --> 01:30:06.000
Well you got your job back.

01:30:06.000 --> 01:30:08.000
Okay we're back after short break.

01:30:08.000 --> 01:30:12.000
You know what I got in my job but let me just back up make this point.

01:30:12.000 --> 01:30:22.000
And getting the job they ran me around from the revenue building which was like two blocks west of the state capital.

01:30:22.000 --> 01:30:28.000
Back to the state capital about three or four times it was hot.

01:30:28.000 --> 01:30:34.000
And they were paving the asphalt which made it even hotter and smelly.

01:30:34.000 --> 01:30:42.000
So after about the second time me walking down there and walking back walking down there and walking back.

01:30:42.000 --> 01:30:44.000
I decided to take my shoes off.

01:30:44.000 --> 01:30:49.000
Not knowing what was going to happen to my feet.

01:30:49.000 --> 01:30:58.000
But after I walked down there barefooted and walked back there was a young man on the state capital grounds that knew me.

01:30:58.000 --> 01:31:00.000
White man.

01:31:00.000 --> 01:31:04.000
He said aren't you Howard Himmelbaum's wife and I said yes.

01:31:04.000 --> 01:31:08.000
He said why are you walking with your shoes off?

01:31:08.000 --> 01:31:11.000
So I began to explain to him who was going on.

01:31:11.000 --> 01:31:15.000
He just sat there and observed everything.

01:31:15.000 --> 01:31:21.000
And he put it in the paper.

01:31:21.000 --> 01:31:29.000
The paper that he worked for wasn't the Arkansas Democrat or the Arkansas Gazette which is now the Arkansas Democrat.

01:31:29.000 --> 01:31:32.000
Wasn't either one of them was another freelance paper.

01:31:32.000 --> 01:31:35.000
Maybe in the Arkansas Times I'm not sure.

01:31:35.000 --> 01:31:43.000
But he put it in there so that people would hear about it and he called Howard to tell him what was going on.

01:31:43.000 --> 01:31:48.000
The story that he wrote was about how you were getting the run around the state.

01:31:48.000 --> 01:31:52.000
And you were taking the shoes off just because my feet were getting tired.

01:31:52.000 --> 01:31:56.000
Have you been to the state capital?

01:31:56.000 --> 01:32:03.000
And it took me like weeks to get all the black tar off my bottom of my feet by the way.

01:32:03.000 --> 01:32:17.000
But when they finally got the idea that this woman is determined that she's not going away, they decided to give me the test there at the state capital and the administration office.

01:32:17.000 --> 01:32:25.000
And what they gave me, the test on was something that I could have done with my eyes closed literally.

01:32:25.000 --> 01:32:28.000
They gave me 30 minutes to take the test.

01:32:28.000 --> 01:32:35.000
I had to program my own card and do all this, which I was very proficient at.

01:32:35.000 --> 01:32:39.000
I did all that and it took the test four times and I still had time left.

01:32:39.000 --> 01:32:46.000
I just got tired of taking the stock.

01:32:46.000 --> 01:32:51.000
I got hired to go to work for the Motor Vehicle Department.

01:32:51.000 --> 01:32:58.000
After he fired me and he got me to rehired me, then I actually began to work there in the administration office until I quit.

01:32:58.000 --> 01:33:02.000
And then there's the irony, as you say, you go to work in the capital. It's the first half of the American working.

01:33:02.000 --> 01:33:07.000
And you've got this Republican governor elected with all this black support, which is what gets him into the office.

01:33:07.000 --> 01:33:11.000
And then you can't even capture it.

01:33:11.000 --> 01:33:15.000
So it was quite an experience though.

01:33:15.000 --> 01:33:22.000
And then you and Howard continue your involvement, because as you say, you're going to be in Memphis in 1968.

01:33:22.000 --> 01:33:26.000
Well, it's just...

01:33:26.000 --> 01:33:32.000
We still formerly, I mean SNCC is really beginning to come apart in 1967-68.

01:33:32.000 --> 01:33:43.000
Yeah, but I mean, men, who stayed married until 1978, I believe, was.

01:33:43.000 --> 01:33:49.000
I worked most of that time.

01:33:49.000 --> 01:33:53.000
But I know what I did.

01:33:53.000 --> 01:33:59.000
After I left the state capital, I went and put in an application with Kelly Services.

01:33:59.000 --> 01:34:02.000
So I could work part-time.

01:34:02.000 --> 01:34:08.000
The way I could not take a job or take a job.

01:34:08.000 --> 01:34:12.000
And that worked out fine for me until I got to that point.

01:34:12.000 --> 01:34:18.000
You know that I wanted my own car. I wanted this. You know how it happens.

01:34:18.000 --> 01:34:29.000
And so I wound up going to work for American life insurance company, I believe, was what it was called.

01:34:29.000 --> 01:34:37.000
I worked for them a couple of years, and then I went to work for Southwestern Bell and worked for them for 14 years.

01:34:37.000 --> 01:34:54.000
But doing that time between probably 68-69 to 71, it was active in the BUY Black United Youth.

01:34:54.000 --> 01:35:00.000
Then traveling to Memphis Atlanta, West Tellenham, McGehee, Arkansas.

01:35:00.000 --> 01:35:10.000
Earle, Arkansas, I was in Earle, Arkansas the night that they had decided they was going to force the Black Children to go to.

01:35:10.000 --> 01:35:18.000
They closed the Black High School and forced their body to go to the White High School.

01:35:18.000 --> 01:35:25.000
Because of the Black United Youth Group, people were coming to Little Rock, Arkansas asking us for help.

01:35:25.000 --> 01:35:28.000
We would go to support them.

01:35:28.000 --> 01:35:34.000
And it was probably a good thing we were there because I mean they beat people that night.

01:35:34.000 --> 01:35:39.000
I was walking by this little old lady and this state trooper came in between us.

01:35:39.000 --> 01:35:43.000
And he had his three-fifth of said, Magnum up gone.

01:35:43.000 --> 01:35:47.000
He pulled his trigger and said, Ron Nigger, pow, Ron Nigger.

01:35:47.000 --> 01:35:50.000
And this little old lady on this walking cane, right?

01:35:50.000 --> 01:35:55.000
And he finally reached over and knocked to walking cane out of the mud and knocked.

01:35:55.000 --> 01:35:58.000
And I was like, do this man send me over here?

01:35:58.000 --> 01:36:02.000
Because he act just like he didn't even see me.

01:36:02.000 --> 01:36:06.000
And they were going behind bushes and beating people and I'm walking.

01:36:06.000 --> 01:36:15.000
And then this pickup truck comes by, people running, polis shooting, just to scare people.

01:36:15.000 --> 01:36:18.000
Because I guess they knew we didn't have any weapons or stuff.

01:36:18.000 --> 01:36:20.000
But we really did have weapons.

01:36:20.000 --> 01:36:24.000
But they weren't with us. They were in our car.

01:36:24.000 --> 01:36:28.000
So we got back to the house.

01:36:28.000 --> 01:36:34.000
I believe Ed, Larry Dixon and Eric was with us.

01:36:34.000 --> 01:36:43.000
Robert Brawwater, myself, a young woman named Katanga.

01:36:43.000 --> 01:36:47.000
And we got back to the house where we had started from.

01:36:47.000 --> 01:36:53.000
Of course, everybody had their guns out in Earl.

01:36:53.000 --> 01:36:59.000
And I don't remember exactly what year that was, but it was the year they desegregated the high schools.

01:36:59.000 --> 01:37:04.000
And of course, like I said, they closed the black high school left the white one open.

01:37:04.000 --> 01:37:12.000
And we got back to Little Rock, Arkansas that I had been picked up by these white men on the pickup truck.

01:37:12.000 --> 01:37:15.000
And they drove off with it.

01:37:15.000 --> 01:37:20.000
So I turned the walker called the governor and the governor sent out the state,

01:37:20.000 --> 01:37:25.000
the National Guard to go down and see what was going on and everything.

01:37:25.000 --> 01:37:33.000
So they got back to Little Rock, Arkansas because I actually, I became an expert driver because of the movement.

01:37:33.000 --> 01:37:37.000
And we were driving a Mustang.

01:37:37.000 --> 01:37:40.000
My friend Bob Brawwater had a Mustang.

01:37:40.000 --> 01:37:43.000
And he said, carry you driving. I'm riding shotgun.

01:37:43.000 --> 01:37:46.000
It was about four or five hours in the car.

01:37:46.000 --> 01:37:50.000
I drove, got out of there and got back.

01:37:50.000 --> 01:37:56.000
And Howard said, John W. Walker got the National Guard head of the turtle looking for you.

01:37:56.000 --> 01:37:59.000
So he said, you better get on the phone and call him.

01:37:59.000 --> 01:38:02.000
Because he hadn't picked up a gun.

01:38:02.000 --> 01:38:07.000
But the way they were driving, they were driving and knocking people over and stuff like this.

01:38:07.000 --> 01:38:10.000
And I had it where it got to him that it happened.

01:38:10.000 --> 01:38:13.000
But I called him and they didn't know what was going on.

01:38:13.000 --> 01:38:19.000
And then of course they wanted to meet with all of us and find out exactly what had happened and everything.

01:38:19.000 --> 01:38:21.000
I mean, it was a crazy thing.

01:38:21.000 --> 01:38:27.000
All the marches I had been in, I had never seen anything go as haywire as that.

01:38:27.000 --> 01:38:36.000
And through no provocation of anybody that was there, the police just decided they wanted to be bullets.

01:38:36.000 --> 01:38:42.000
Tell me, can you tell me about Bobby Brown and the BUY.?

01:38:42.000 --> 01:38:45.000
Bobby Brown was like a...

01:38:45.000 --> 01:38:54.000
The philosophy was just to protect the black youth, especially in the college environment.

01:38:54.000 --> 01:39:00.000
Make sure that they had a student union representation.

01:39:00.000 --> 01:39:09.000
And you probably aware of that being from Chapel Hill because that was one of the things that they were fighting for when I went to do them.

01:39:09.000 --> 01:39:23.000
Having black leadership within that system, not just putting our children into the institutions of how I learned and have no representation or consideration for that matter.

01:39:24.000 --> 01:39:26.000
That's basically what it was all about.

01:39:26.000 --> 01:39:35.000
And it had to also start in the high schools since we were now integrating or desegregating all of the schools from all levels.

01:39:35.000 --> 01:39:38.000
It needed to be in the high schools as well.

01:39:38.000 --> 01:39:48.000
That was our focus and we were trying to get the students to come home and share what's going on in the schools that you know is not right.

01:39:48.000 --> 01:39:54.000
If you feel like your teacher is not treating you properly, come share that.

01:39:54.000 --> 01:39:57.000
I think the parents kind of blocked that.

01:39:57.000 --> 01:40:09.000
We had a few young men that come in, especially from what we call the south end of Little Rock, Arkansas and a few from West Little Rock, Arkansas.

01:40:10.000 --> 01:40:20.000
Because their parents seemed to be economically more secure than the children that was in East Little Rock, Arkansas.

01:40:20.000 --> 01:40:24.000
East Little Rock, Arkansas was your more poor class of people.

01:40:24.000 --> 01:40:36.000
College Station was kind of an isolated black community of its own that was very strong economically and spiritually.

01:40:37.000 --> 01:40:40.000
And it used to this day.

01:40:40.000 --> 01:40:47.000
And Bobby Brown.

01:40:47.000 --> 01:40:49.000
That was Bobbi.

01:40:49.000 --> 01:40:52.000
And Bobbi had influence of the street guys.

01:40:52.000 --> 01:40:55.000
The street guys were really, really tough.

01:40:55.000 --> 01:41:03.000
So Bobby Brown from Little Rock, Arkansas, Bob Broadway from Blackwood, which is like Northeast Arkansas,

01:41:03.000 --> 01:41:10.000
who was also a graduate of Philander Smith College.

01:41:10.000 --> 01:41:11.000
He was a little.

01:41:11.000 --> 01:41:12.000
Yes.

01:41:12.000 --> 01:41:13.000
And he was married.

01:41:13.000 --> 01:41:15.000
His wife was a teacher.

01:41:15.000 --> 01:41:20.000
And he was a news announcer with KOKY-AM, radio station.

01:41:20.000 --> 01:41:23.000
Let's take a little break.

01:41:23.000 --> 01:41:25.000
We're back after short break for the phone.

01:41:25.000 --> 01:41:30.000
Just describing Bob.

01:41:30.000 --> 01:41:31.000
Was it Broadway?

01:41:31.000 --> 01:41:33.000
And KOKY-AM White.

01:41:33.000 --> 01:41:34.000
Yes.

01:41:34.000 --> 01:41:41.000
He was a grad by, Broadway was a Philander Smith College.

01:41:41.000 --> 01:41:49.000
He worked at KOKY-AM White at the time I met him under the directorship of a man named Larry Hayes.

01:41:50.000 --> 01:42:01.000
And both he and Larry were focused on bringing a black perspective to the media.

01:42:01.000 --> 01:42:06.000
So that people would know exactly what was going on.

01:42:06.000 --> 01:42:13.000
And because of that, him and Bobby Brown became our collaborators together.

01:42:13.000 --> 01:42:18.000
But of course, Bob Broadway, the being from where he was from,

01:42:18.000 --> 01:42:24.000
he was interested in becoming and planning active part in the movement as well.

01:42:24.000 --> 01:42:28.000
So they kind of had some little clashes too, power struggles.

01:42:28.000 --> 01:42:35.000
Mainly because Bobby Brown was like hated white folks.

01:42:35.000 --> 01:42:39.000
I mean, I just put it out there.

01:42:39.000 --> 01:42:45.000
His thing was I hate white folks all on a hand and do it.

01:42:45.000 --> 01:42:46.000
And we're all white as man.

01:42:46.000 --> 01:42:51.000
We can't work in this world without all the people.

01:42:51.000 --> 01:42:54.000
And we have to learn how to work with each other.

01:42:54.000 --> 01:43:02.000
And we battle that through getting (Winthrop) Rockefeller elected as governor.

01:43:02.000 --> 01:43:06.000
We had factions going on on the inside and stuff like that.

01:43:06.000 --> 01:43:11.000
But dealing with what is our alternative?

01:43:11.000 --> 01:43:16.000
Okay, let's go talk to (Winthrop) Rockefeller, I'll say.

01:43:16.000 --> 01:43:18.000
Let's get to Urban League out the way.

01:43:18.000 --> 01:43:22.000
Let's get the Arkansas Council on Human Relations out the way.

01:43:22.000 --> 01:43:26.000
Because we don't want nobody selling our vote.

01:43:26.000 --> 01:43:30.000
We deal with that today.

01:43:30.000 --> 01:43:36.000
And John W. Walker W. Walker was involved in all these negotiations as well.

01:43:36.000 --> 01:43:41.000
And he was struggling today.

01:43:41.000 --> 01:43:46.000
If you allow certain people to take your words to establish things,

01:43:46.000 --> 01:43:48.000
then you get booted out.

01:43:48.000 --> 01:43:50.000
And the people don't get served.

01:43:50.000 --> 01:43:57.000
So that was our concern and our focus that if we're going to elect this man, governor,

01:43:57.000 --> 01:44:03.000
he needs to know what it is that we want, not what y'all want, but what we want.

01:44:04.000 --> 01:44:13.000
Bobby, he was a good bodyguard.

01:44:13.000 --> 01:44:24.000
He had that possess that was needed for any struggle, for any person in power.

01:44:24.000 --> 01:44:32.000
You need somebody that can have the strong arm and know how to communicate to him.

01:44:32.000 --> 01:44:41.000
I don't think he was ever able to really bring his vision to the community

01:44:41.000 --> 01:44:44.000
where people could receive him.

01:44:44.000 --> 01:44:53.000
But there were those of us, and I was one, I respected him for what he brought to the table.

01:44:53.000 --> 01:45:01.000
His sister was like a forerunner because of her participation in the Little Rock, Arkansas nine and everything.

01:45:01.000 --> 01:45:05.000
I know his family had gone through a lot because of that.

01:45:05.000 --> 01:45:14.000
People made, after years, appreciate what happened as a result when you're in it, they're afraid.

01:45:14.000 --> 01:45:21.000
And sometimes even the silence is worse than those who are speaking out.

01:45:21.000 --> 01:45:25.000
And I know that affected him.

01:45:25.000 --> 01:45:28.000
What took you down to Memphis in six years?

01:45:28.000 --> 01:45:30.000
Just a few years, Dr. King?

01:45:30.000 --> 01:45:37.000
Not so much to hear him is to support him, to be there for protection, to be eyes and ears.

01:45:37.000 --> 01:45:45.000
That's basically what we did to increase the view.

01:45:45.000 --> 01:45:51.000
A lot of times they didn't want the sisters there because they knew when Dr. King showed up on the scene

01:45:51.000 --> 01:45:54.000
there were going to be guns aimed at him.

01:45:54.000 --> 01:45:57.000
They knew that.

01:45:57.000 --> 01:46:07.000
And like I said earlier, that's why the Black Liberation Army came, that's why the Black Panther movement came.

01:46:07.000 --> 01:46:11.000
It was for the protection of a leader, nothing else.

01:46:11.000 --> 01:46:14.000
It wasn't to go out and kill white folks.

01:46:14.000 --> 01:46:17.000
It was for protection of a leader.

01:46:17.000 --> 01:46:29.000
We may not have agreed with all of Dr. King's methods of getting where he wanted to go, but we didn't want to see him dead.

01:46:29.000 --> 01:46:35.000
And we all played a part in the struggle and got things accomplished in our own way.

01:46:35.000 --> 01:46:40.000
And the wrong people were the closest to him.

01:46:40.000 --> 01:46:46.000
That's all I can say because if the right people had been closest to him, I think he would have lived a little longer.

01:46:46.000 --> 01:46:50.000
But you can do that bit.

01:46:50.000 --> 01:46:57.000
What was your opinion of mine in the late 60s after Dr. King has killed?

01:46:57.000 --> 01:47:00.000
And you're obviously married to a white man.

01:47:00.000 --> 01:47:04.000
You've met in the movement.

01:47:04.000 --> 01:47:09.000
But the movement has changed quite a bit by the late 60s from its early form.

01:47:09.000 --> 01:47:19.000
Can you recall your sense of perspective on this society if its prospects were very positive?

01:47:19.000 --> 01:47:23.000
I didn't see.

01:47:23.000 --> 01:47:30.000
I saw some change, but I didn't see the change I wanted to see.

01:47:30.000 --> 01:47:33.000
Wrong people got in office.

01:47:33.000 --> 01:47:41.000
Wrong people got the best paying jobs in corporate America.

01:47:41.000 --> 01:47:44.000
People got access to high education.

01:47:44.000 --> 01:47:59.000
And in all those three categories I just named, I think people very casually forget where they came from and how they got the way they were.

01:47:59.000 --> 01:48:02.000
The story was not kept alive.

01:48:02.000 --> 01:48:15.000
And those of us who wanted to continue to talk about it like a Bobby Brown or Carrie Himmelbaum, we got put down or pushed to the side.

01:48:15.000 --> 01:48:18.000
Don't want to hear that.

01:48:18.000 --> 01:48:20.000
America is OK now.

01:48:20.000 --> 01:48:24.000
But now we're in 2011 and we know that America is not OK.

01:48:24.000 --> 01:48:31.000
What changes did you put that the movement would produce that one emerging?

01:48:31.000 --> 01:48:37.000
My personal was economic change.

01:48:37.000 --> 01:48:42.000
Blacks in business.

01:48:42.000 --> 01:48:46.000
To have the same access.

01:48:46.000 --> 01:48:50.000
My struggle was not about being as good as the white man.

01:48:50.000 --> 01:48:57.000
My struggle was about, and I think everybody was and people lost focus on it.

01:48:57.000 --> 01:49:00.000
It was about civil rights.

01:49:00.000 --> 01:49:07.000
It was about holding up the Constitution of the United States of America.

01:49:07.000 --> 01:49:16.000
And I saw a shift when people began to come back from the Vietnam War.

01:49:16.000 --> 01:49:22.000
I saw a major shift because of the drugs that came with it.

01:49:22.000 --> 01:49:26.000
White America became addicted to drugs.

01:49:26.000 --> 01:49:30.000
They had to stand before the judge just like black people did.

01:49:30.000 --> 01:49:36.000
And white people changed the law to protect their children.

01:49:36.000 --> 01:49:38.000
That's what I saw.

01:49:38.000 --> 01:49:40.000
That's what I see today.

01:49:40.000 --> 01:49:45.000
They just killed Troy Davis.

01:49:45.000 --> 01:49:49.000
No evidence whatsoever.

01:49:49.000 --> 01:49:58.000
That's not a country that's growing.

01:49:58.000 --> 01:50:04.000
And those are the things that people should be talking about.

01:50:04.000 --> 01:50:09.000
Not only black people should have been out in the yard, but all people should have been out in the yard.

01:50:09.000 --> 01:50:12.000
No, we're not going to let you do that.

01:50:12.000 --> 01:50:14.000
You can't do that.

01:50:14.000 --> 01:50:16.000
This is 2011.

01:50:16.000 --> 01:50:22.000
We don't kill people without evidence.

01:50:22.000 --> 01:50:24.000
This is a man just for the record.

01:50:24.000 --> 01:50:28.000
This is a man who was executed last week in Georgia by Georgia State authorities

01:50:28.000 --> 01:50:33.000
who were reportedly murdered 22 years ago.

01:50:33.000 --> 01:50:37.000
Everyone up to and including the former Republican, Attorney General, United States,

01:50:37.000 --> 01:50:43.000
petition and state not to move forward with the execution.

01:50:43.000 --> 01:50:52.000
How long did you, moving into the 1970s, how long did you have an organized framework for continuing your activism?

01:50:52.000 --> 01:50:57.000
How long did the UI persist in an organized form?

01:50:57.000 --> 01:51:07.000
I believe up until about 1970, 1971, somewhere in there.

01:51:07.000 --> 01:51:15.000
Did you have organized vehicles after that?

01:51:15.000 --> 01:51:17.000
No, no more so then.

01:51:17.000 --> 01:51:21.000
Most of the things seemed to generate out of Atlanta.

01:51:21.000 --> 01:51:34.000
You had the SCLC that had been developed, but that's Southern Christian Leadership Conference.

01:51:34.000 --> 01:51:37.000
And there was another group too.

01:51:37.000 --> 01:51:44.000
And it's like everything merged into Atlanta and kind of went out from there.

01:51:44.000 --> 01:51:50.000
Floyd McKissick, you know, and then of course,

01:51:50.000 --> 01:51:55.000
Julian Bond went into politics and Andrew Young went into politics,

01:51:55.000 --> 01:51:59.000
Marion Barry went into politics.

01:51:59.000 --> 01:52:07.000
And it's, you know, again, it's like the vision was lost with them.

01:52:07.000 --> 01:52:13.000
These were great opportunities that we missed.

01:52:13.000 --> 01:52:16.000
How did you read Obama's election?

01:52:16.000 --> 01:52:22.000
How did I read it?

01:52:22.000 --> 01:52:25.000
Can I set an end word on here?

01:52:25.000 --> 01:52:28.000
Sure.

01:52:28.000 --> 01:52:33.000
I saw in Little Rock, Arkansas looking from Little Rock, Arkansas,

01:52:33.000 --> 01:52:42.000
but I could do it nationally, but from a personal perspective,

01:52:42.000 --> 01:52:50.000
I saw an omnis in Little Rock, Arkansas.

01:52:50.000 --> 01:52:58.000
I didn't see people looking at a man who had achieved acceptance

01:52:58.000 --> 01:53:03.000
at a political leader and a possibility to run this country.

01:53:03.000 --> 01:53:09.000
It was like there was just a flat out refusal to even look at him

01:53:09.000 --> 01:53:13.000
until after the primary.

01:53:13.000 --> 01:53:18.000
And I met a fact I sent out an email last week

01:53:18.000 --> 01:53:22.000
in a response to a big blast that somebody put out about us coming together

01:53:22.000 --> 01:53:25.000
and supporting Obama.

01:53:25.000 --> 01:53:28.000
And I suggested that we put our money where our mouth is,

01:53:28.000 --> 01:53:33.000
because number one, that's the first thing he needs to be reelected.

01:53:33.000 --> 01:53:37.000
And then I shared with them how I felt threatened

01:53:37.000 --> 01:53:40.000
when he first ran for office.

01:53:40.000 --> 01:53:45.000
When I read about him running and I knew the things

01:53:45.000 --> 01:53:49.000
that he had already tried to do and accomplished as a political figure

01:53:49.000 --> 01:53:53.000
in America and in the state of Illinois,

01:53:53.000 --> 01:53:55.000
I said, you know what?

01:53:55.000 --> 01:53:59.000
I can't find any reason why I shouldn't support this man.

01:53:59.000 --> 01:54:04.000
After all, I have struggled for in America to get blacks in a position like this.

01:54:04.000 --> 01:54:08.000
He fit every category, okay?

01:54:08.000 --> 01:54:11.000
And I was offended in several areas.

01:54:11.000 --> 01:54:16.000
The first one I was offended in is that we would ask him for a resume.

01:54:16.000 --> 01:54:21.000
In 60 years of my life, I've never heard of a president

01:54:21.000 --> 01:54:25.000
or a person running for president asked to get a resume.

01:54:25.000 --> 01:54:27.000
You need a resume?

01:54:27.000 --> 01:54:32.000
No, resume. He was asked for a resume.

01:54:32.000 --> 01:54:36.000
The birth certificate came later.

01:54:36.000 --> 01:54:42.000
I mean, the only resume you ever spoke about

01:54:42.000 --> 01:54:45.000
needed to be an American citizen, right?

01:54:45.000 --> 01:54:47.000
Born in America, rather, and beat what?

01:54:47.000 --> 01:54:50.000
21, 40.

01:54:50.000 --> 01:54:54.000
And he met him.

01:54:54.000 --> 01:54:57.000
As long as he was senator,

01:54:57.000 --> 01:55:00.000
wasn't nobody questioning where he was from.

01:55:00.000 --> 01:55:02.000
You know what I'm saying?

01:55:02.000 --> 01:55:04.000
When you were saying the numbness,

01:55:04.000 --> 01:55:06.000
are you saying the black community?

01:55:06.000 --> 01:55:08.000
Certainly in the white community.

01:55:08.000 --> 01:55:10.000
I think I'm saying in the black community.

01:55:10.000 --> 01:55:12.000
In the black community here,

01:55:12.000 --> 01:55:16.000
maybe it's just because this is a clinton favor or something.

01:55:16.000 --> 01:55:22.000
So I had, and they're going to come out here and love it.

01:55:22.000 --> 01:55:24.000
But I have my box of memorabilia

01:55:24.000 --> 01:55:28.000
where I went online to the Democratic website

01:55:28.000 --> 01:55:31.000
and ordered little flag from my vehicle

01:55:31.000 --> 01:55:35.000
and signs from my windows and all this stuff.

01:55:35.000 --> 01:55:37.000
And I would drive down the streets

01:55:37.000 --> 01:55:40.000
and people would look at me like I was crazy.

01:55:40.000 --> 01:55:42.000
I got asked to be quiet in a place,

01:55:42.000 --> 01:55:45.000
a public place that I spent money

01:55:45.000 --> 01:55:48.000
to get my taxes prepared every year

01:55:48.000 --> 01:55:52.000
because I was talking about Obama in a positive way.

01:55:52.000 --> 01:55:55.000
Wow.

01:55:56.000 --> 01:55:58.000
I'm going to show one more time.

01:55:58.000 --> 01:56:01.000
I'm going to start with this one.

01:56:01.000 --> 01:56:03.000
Okay, we're back.

01:56:03.000 --> 01:56:05.000
We have, we're back after short break

01:56:05.000 --> 01:56:07.000
and we have a swap of drives,

01:56:07.000 --> 01:56:09.000
hard drives further recording.

01:56:09.000 --> 01:56:12.000
Miss Young, we're talking about President Obama.

01:56:12.000 --> 01:56:13.000
And President Obama,

01:56:13.000 --> 01:56:21.000
one thing I would like to say,

01:56:21.000 --> 01:56:25.000
is overall I support him.

01:56:25.000 --> 01:56:29.000
And I'll say this with no hesitation.

01:56:29.000 --> 01:56:32.000
The main reason I supported President Obama

01:56:32.000 --> 01:56:36.000
is because he was a black man that was qualified.

01:56:36.000 --> 01:56:41.000
Number two, I don't agree with everything President Obama has done

01:56:41.000 --> 01:56:45.000
and I probably won't agree with everything he'll do in the future.

01:56:45.000 --> 01:56:47.000
But no other President

01:56:47.000 --> 01:56:51.000
have I had the opportunity to vote for.

01:56:51.000 --> 01:56:55.000
Have I ever agreed with everything that he said it did?

01:56:55.000 --> 01:56:57.000
Okay.

01:56:57.000 --> 01:57:00.000
And I would say this to black America.

01:57:00.000 --> 01:57:08.000
If you can't usher yourself into a spirit of support

01:57:08.000 --> 01:57:12.000
and cooperation with President Barack Obama

01:57:12.000 --> 01:57:15.000
and you'll probably hear this after the fact.

01:57:15.000 --> 01:57:19.000
But if you didn't, you need to examine yourself

01:57:19.000 --> 01:57:23.000
because you miss one of the greatest opportunities of your life.

01:57:23.000 --> 01:57:27.000
Our parents died for this day.

01:57:27.000 --> 01:57:29.000
Our children have died for this day.

01:57:29.000 --> 01:57:34.000
Both black, white, Jew, Indian, Chinese, what have you?

01:57:34.000 --> 01:57:39.000
Have died for the day to have a black man as a President

01:57:39.000 --> 01:57:41.000
of the United States of America.

01:57:41.000 --> 01:57:45.000
And for us not to have supported him the way we could have.

01:57:45.000 --> 01:57:48.000
And what we lacked admitted or not,

01:57:48.000 --> 01:57:53.000
we have done some deliberate things to hinder prosperity

01:57:53.000 --> 01:57:57.000
and success in America in the last three years.

01:57:57.000 --> 01:57:59.000
Can't deny.

01:58:03.000 --> 01:58:06.000
I think as a President,

01:58:06.000 --> 01:58:10.000
I would have loved to see him be a stronger Christian.

01:58:10.000 --> 01:58:18.000
And not sign some of the things into a law that he has

01:58:18.000 --> 01:58:24.000
because they just go against Christianity.

01:58:28.000 --> 01:58:33.000
I think people's freedom of speech

01:58:33.000 --> 01:58:38.000
have been compromised for the hate word.

01:58:38.000 --> 01:58:43.000
But I think it's a trick of the devil.

01:58:43.000 --> 01:58:47.000
And people need to fight for their liberty to speak

01:58:47.000 --> 01:58:50.000
whatever they want to speak.

01:58:50.000 --> 01:58:58.000
And we should be mature enough to either hear it or tune it up.

01:58:58.000 --> 01:59:00.000
As a black woman in America,

01:59:00.000 --> 01:59:03.000
I've had to deal with that all my life.

01:59:03.000 --> 01:59:07.000
So if I want to call a person a faggot

01:59:07.000 --> 01:59:12.000
I shouldn't have to worry about going to jail for that.

01:59:12.000 --> 01:59:17.000
That's part of my freedom of speech.

01:59:17.000 --> 01:59:22.000
If I want to call somebody a nigger,

01:59:22.000 --> 01:59:25.000
that's part of my freedom of speech.

01:59:25.000 --> 01:59:28.000
My dad called my mom that all the time.

01:59:28.000 --> 01:59:30.000
It's a pet word, okay?

01:59:30.000 --> 01:59:34.000
So it's about the hero and the giver

01:59:34.000 --> 01:59:38.000
and the state that is being used in.

01:59:38.000 --> 01:59:43.000
But because America is so called up today

01:59:43.000 --> 01:59:46.000
having a black person in office

01:59:46.000 --> 01:59:51.000
they want to cut off every liberty you can think of.

01:59:51.000 --> 01:59:55.000
Let me ask you about your year in Durham.

01:59:55.000 --> 01:59:58.000
I think it was 1971.

01:59:58.000 --> 02:00:03.000
It was interesting.

02:00:03.000 --> 02:00:09.000
I had several reasons for one to go.

02:00:09.000 --> 02:00:22.000
I think a lot of my reasoning had to do with acceptance.

02:00:22.000 --> 02:00:25.000
Had nothing to do with the fact that I was married to a white man

02:00:25.000 --> 02:00:29.000
at the time because I was married to Howard Himmelbaum at the time.

02:00:29.000 --> 02:00:32.000
Part of it was acceptance.

02:00:32.000 --> 02:00:35.000
I needed to know black folks.

02:00:35.000 --> 02:00:38.000
The black folks that I knew growing up in West Helena, Arkansas

02:00:38.000 --> 02:00:41.000
didn't like me.

02:00:41.000 --> 02:00:45.000
There you go.

02:00:45.000 --> 02:00:52.000
Now with people who are supposed to be fighting for equal rights

02:00:52.000 --> 02:00:57.000
and leveraging justice for all.

02:00:57.000 --> 02:01:01.000
I had to understand that just because the name of the school

02:01:01.000 --> 02:01:05.000
was Malcolm X Liberation University wasn't a black white thing.

02:01:05.000 --> 02:01:10.000
But it's about education.

02:01:10.000 --> 02:01:12.000
And understanding who you are.

02:01:12.000 --> 02:01:15.000
We actually studied the different races

02:01:15.000 --> 02:01:21.000
and the different ethnic groups in Africa and Mexico.

02:01:21.000 --> 02:01:24.000
We learned martial arts.

02:01:24.000 --> 02:01:30.000
We learned about self-control and all this.

02:01:30.000 --> 02:01:35.000
We looked for opportunities in the community to participate

02:01:35.000 --> 02:01:38.000
in different things where we could support.

02:01:38.000 --> 02:01:42.000
We even came to Chapel Hill a couple of times with some activities

02:01:42.000 --> 02:01:48.000
that was going on over there and participating in those things.

02:01:48.000 --> 02:01:53.000
But even there, people couldn't see past color.

02:01:53.000 --> 02:01:56.000
And I had a couple of people that didn't appreciate

02:01:56.000 --> 02:01:58.000
when my husband came to visit me.

02:01:58.000 --> 02:02:01.000
I think it was either Thanksgiving or Christmas.

02:02:01.000 --> 02:02:04.000
So I'm the people that didn't know that I was married to a white guy

02:02:04.000 --> 02:02:07.000
so it became an issue.

02:02:07.000 --> 02:02:09.000
So I said, you know what?

02:02:09.000 --> 02:02:12.000
It's time for me to go.

02:02:12.000 --> 02:02:15.000
Because it's where racism is.

02:02:15.000 --> 02:02:18.000
I don't want to be there.

02:02:18.000 --> 02:02:24.000
We are all created in God's image.

02:02:24.000 --> 02:02:27.000
And that's how I look at people.

02:02:27.000 --> 02:02:29.000
I try not to see white and black.

02:02:29.000 --> 02:02:32.000
And if you bring it up, I might look at you and say,

02:02:32.000 --> 02:02:35.000
do you believe that Jesus is a Christ?

02:02:35.000 --> 02:02:37.000
If you don't believe Jesus is a Christ,

02:02:37.000 --> 02:02:39.000
I say, oh, then you are white.

02:02:39.000 --> 02:02:42.000
And that's the way I'll treat you.

02:02:42.000 --> 02:02:45.000
But if you tell me you believe Jesus is a Christ,

02:02:45.000 --> 02:02:48.000
I can't see you white.

02:02:48.000 --> 02:02:54.000
Because if you don't have to understand it, it's going to come.

02:02:54.000 --> 02:02:57.000
I have one remaining question too.

02:02:57.000 --> 02:03:03.000
But are there other issues that we haven't touched on that you'd like to touch on?

02:03:03.000 --> 02:03:06.000
No, I don't think so.

02:03:06.000 --> 02:03:09.000
I'd like to say this.

02:03:09.000 --> 02:03:14.000
It's having the opportunity to sit here and be interviewed by you all.

02:03:14.000 --> 02:03:20.000
I would like to thank Murdered Lasco and people like her

02:03:20.000 --> 02:03:25.000
who understands that there are people like me out here in the field

02:03:25.000 --> 02:03:31.000
who gave all they had to give to the struggle of equal rights for all men

02:03:31.000 --> 02:03:35.000
and women, not only in America, but in the world.

02:03:35.000 --> 02:03:40.000
And I thank you, gentlemen, for doing a fantastic job.

02:03:40.000 --> 02:03:42.000
I'm sure if you think of something when you get home,

02:03:42.000 --> 02:03:45.000
that you left out, you know, you can feel free to call me

02:03:45.000 --> 02:03:48.000
and we can elaborate on it later date.

02:03:48.000 --> 02:03:53.000
But I'd just like to thank the Lord for this opportunity.

02:03:53.000 --> 02:03:56.000
And thank the Lord for a wonderful director that I have

02:03:56.000 --> 02:04:00.000
in Modern Woodmen of America named Albert Hurst Jr.

02:04:00.000 --> 02:04:02.000
Albert T. Hurst Jr.

02:04:02.000 --> 02:04:07.000
who gave me time off to come home and do this interview with you all.

02:04:08.000 --> 02:04:11.000
One final question on our side.

02:04:11.000 --> 02:04:14.000
It's sort of a point of personal privilege,

02:04:14.000 --> 02:04:16.000
but also connects to the movement.

02:04:16.000 --> 02:04:19.000
You knew someone John W. Walker knew, and that was worth long.

02:04:19.000 --> 02:04:20.000
Oh, yes.

02:04:20.000 --> 02:04:24.000
The description of work.

02:04:24.000 --> 02:04:31.000
Worth Long was an art man, a sweet man.

02:04:31.000 --> 02:04:36.000
But he danced to a shownut of different beat.

02:04:36.000 --> 02:04:42.000
He was always very pleasant, very respectful.

02:04:42.000 --> 02:04:49.000
He kind of flowed with the wind, you know, when he was around you.

02:04:49.000 --> 02:04:54.000
He always had a little bag on his arm.

02:04:54.000 --> 02:04:57.000
And he was just always pleasant.

02:04:57.000 --> 02:05:02.000
He really was.

02:05:02.000 --> 02:05:07.000
I never really got to know him because he wasn't around that much

02:05:07.000 --> 02:05:11.000
in the area where I was.

02:05:11.000 --> 02:05:13.000
But when he would come to West Helena, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas,

02:05:13.000 --> 02:05:19.000
he would make sure he came to visit my parents.

02:05:19.000 --> 02:05:21.000
Well, it's been a real honor and a privilege.

02:05:21.000 --> 02:05:23.000
Miss Young, thank you so much for the warm welcome.

02:05:23.000 --> 02:05:28.000
And it's been a wonderful thing to set this down for the collection.

02:05:28.000 --> 02:05:29.000
Thank you so much.

02:05:29.000 --> 02:05:31.000
Thank you.

02:05:31.000 --> 02:05:35.000
Oh, I got to see it on it.

02:05:35.000 --> 02:05:38.000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress

02:05:38.000 --> 02:05:45.000
and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

